@ \chapter{Game initialization}

The game entry point is [[GAME_INIT_NOP]], called by the loader's [[FIRST_BOOT]]
via [[JSR GAME_INIT_NOP]]. The first 19 bytes ([[GAME_INIT_NOP]]--[[$4012]]) are NOPs --- the
original copy protection was patched out. The real initialization begins
at [[GAME_INIT]].

\section{HUD/frame unpacker}

[[GAME_INIT]] unpacks a data stream from [[HUD_FRAME_DATA]] into hi-res
page~1 ([[HGR1_BASE]]--[[$3FFF]]), drawing the static HUD and playfield frame
(score panels, lives/level indicators, and wall/floor borders --- \emph{not}
the DROL logo, which is drawn later). The stream consists
of 37 records, each containing a 2-byte destination address (lo/hi)
followed by 40 data bytes. A [[$FF]] terminator ends the stream.

After [[GAME_INIT]] returns, [[FIRST_BOOT]] sets up vectors, detects
the joystick, applies machine-specific patches, restores zero page from
[[ZP_SAVE]], and enters the game via [[JMP (ZP_GAME_ENTRY)]]. The initial
value of [[ZP_GAME_ENTRY]] from [[ZP_SAVE]] is [[START_ATTRACT]], which is in the
swappable level data area loaded from track~5.

The 37 records only touch rows 0--32 and 188--191 of hi-res page~1;
every other scanline is left in whatever state the framebuffer was in
when [[GAME_INIT]] started. Figure~\ref{fig:hud-frame} shows what
the page looks like immediately after [[GAME_INIT]] returns, assuming
a cleared framebuffer: the static score/hiscore HUD, the player-lives
and level indicators, and the purple wall/floor frame of the playfield.
The DROL logo and any other foreground content are drawn later by the
attract-mode sprite routines
[[ATTRACT_ANIM_1]]/[[ATTRACT_ANIM_2]]/[[ATTRACT_ANIM_3]]/[[ATTRACT_ANIM_4]]
which composite sprite pointer tables into hi-res page~2 for the
animated title sequence.

The 237 bytes immediately after the stream terminator
([[SECTOR_RESIDUE_47XX]]--[[$47FF]]) are \emph{dead residue}, not a continuation of the
unpacker --- see [[SECTOR_RESIDUE_47XX]] below.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{images/hud_frame.png}
\caption{Hi-res page~1 contents immediately after [[GAME_INIT]]
returns. Rendered by simulating the unpacker on
[[reference/drol.bin]] and applying Apple~II hi-res palette rules
(see [[.claude/scripts/render_hud_frame.py]]).}
\label{fig:hud-frame}
\end{figure}

<<drol defines>>=

; --- Hi-res page 1 ---
HGR1_BASE       = $2000         ; Hi-res graphics page 1 base address

; --- Zero page (game init) ---
ZP_STREAM       = $A0           ; Data stream pointer (2 bytes)
ZP_UNPACK_DEST  = $A2           ; Unpack destination pointer (2 bytes)
ZP_SAVED_Y      = $A4           ; Saved Y during stream read

; --- Zero page (attract startup) ---
ZP_HGR_SRC      = $29           ; Hi-res copy source pointer (2 bytes)
ZP_HGR_DST      = $2F           ; Hi-res copy destination pointer (2 bytes)

; --- Main loop subroutines (in hex data blocks, not yet disassembled) ---
; (LEVEL_INTRO_TICK has its own ORG chunk)
PAUSE_HANDLER   = $0E51         ; Wait for keypress (pause handler ORG)
; (PLAYER_MOVE_TICK has its own ORG chunk; formerly stubbed as COLLISION_DETECT.)
; (DRAW_PLAYER is the label at ORG DRAW_PLAYER, formerly stubbed as SPRITE_RENDER.)
; (FLOOR_ENEMY_DRAW is the label at ORG FLOOR_ENEMY_DRAW, formerly stubbed
;  as SCORE_DISPLAY.  It is the 4-slot perspective draw sibling of
;  FLOOR_ENEMY_ADVANCE; not a score/HUD routine at all.)
; (SPECIAL_TICK is the label at ORG SPECIAL_TICK, formerly stubbed as SOUND_UPDATE ---
;  misnomer: it ticks the ``special'' sprite slot whose draw lives in phase 3
;  of DRAW_ENTITIES, playing only one sound channel among many.)
; (SPECIAL_DRAW is the label at ORG SPECIAL_DRAW --- formerly stubbed as ANIM_UPDATE ---
;  draws the ``special'' sprite body/puff/inactive-preview and handles its
;  collisions; pairs with SPECIAL_TICK.)
; (COMPANION_UPDATE = $6CFE, exported from companion update chunk)
; (RESCUE_UPDATE is the label at ORG RESCUE_UPDATE, formerly stubbed as
;  LEVEL_LOGIC.  Per-frame tick for the 20-slot rescue-child entity
;  subsystem --- the scoring objective.)
; (RESCUE_DRAW is the label at ORG RESCUE_DRAW, formerly stubbed as
;  PROJECTILE_HANDLER --- the routine is actually the per-frame draw
;  + collision sibling of RESCUE_UPDATE, also responsible for the
;  hostile projectile-spawn path that fires when a rescue child is
;  on the player floor at an odd row.)
; (HAZARD_CHECK has its own ORG chunk)
