\section{Playfield dither source}

The 40-byte span at [[TEXT_STRIP_SRC]] ([[$0300]]--[[$0327]]) holds the
alternating byte pattern [[$55]] / [[$2A]] ([[01010101]]~/~[[00101010]]
in binary).  It is loaded from disk as part of the persistent data
block copied from [[STAGE_VECTORS]] to [[VECTOR_PAGE]] by
[[FIRST_BOOT]], and is treated as read-only data by the game: no
[[STA]] in any shipped routine targets the 40-byte range, so its
contents persist across every level for the entire play session.

\paragraph{Purpose.}
The buffer is consumed one byte per hi-res column ([[X]]=[[$00]]..[[$27]])
by four routines, each of which broadcasts the same column's byte
across every row in a large playfield band:
\begin{itemize}
\item [[CLEAR_PAGE1]]'s [[.text_loop]]: paints the bottom-text area
  (rows 188--199 on page 1, twelve interlaced row bases at
  [[$3028]]..[[$3D50]]).
\item [[CLEAR_PAGE2]]'s [[.text_loop]] /
  [[CLEAR_PAGE2_TEXT_ENTRY]]: the page-2 twin, painting rows
  188--199 on page 2.
\item [[INTERLACE_RESTORE_P1]]: repaints a 105-row, 3-band vertical
  stripe (rows 72--106 / 112--146 / 152--186) through
  [[INTERLACE_FILL_P1]].
\item [[INTERLACE_RESTORE_P2]]: the page-2 twin, same 105 rows.
\end{itemize}
The pair [[$55]]/[[$2A]] encodes a one-pixel-on / one-pixel-off
dot pattern in the Apple II hi-res native 7-dot cell, so broadcasting
alternating bytes across even/odd columns produces a uniform
full-band gray dither --- the playfield's ``empty'' backdrop
between sprites.  Because every band row receives the same
column-indexed byte, the buffer's spatial layout is one dot-pattern
sample per column, repeated vertically.

\paragraph{Why 40 bytes.}
The hi-res framebuffer has 40 bytes per row on the Apple II.  The
buffer is indexed by hi-res column directly (not by screen pixel),
so the natural size is one byte per column of the playfield.  The
alternating [[$55]]/[[$2A]] values fill exactly 20 [[$55]]s and
20 [[$2A]]s, producing an even dither across the 40 columns.

\paragraph{Placement.}
The buffer lives inside the larger [[$02C6]]--[[$03A7]] game-data
blob (emitted by [[<<game data 02C6>>]]), starting at offset [[$3A]]
within that block.  Its [[TEXT_STRIP_SRC]] [[EQU]] is declared in the
[[<<clear page1 defines>>]] chunk alongside the other column-bound
screen-clear constants.

<<lvl init entity hit state data>>=

        ORG $02BA
LVL_INIT_ENTITY_HIT_STATE:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; LVL_INIT_SPRITE[$05..$10] ($02BA-$02C5, 12 bytes of $FF) ---
        ; the per-level seed for the 12-slot ENTITY_HIT_STATE array at
        ; ZP $8D-$98.  INIT_LEVEL_STATE copies LVL_INIT_SPRITE[$00..$2C]
        ; into ZP $88-$B4, so these 12 bytes land at ZP_HIT_STATE[0..11]
        ; and seed every slot to $FF ("inactive").  The array is then
        ; reactivated slot-by-slot by runtime spawns.
        ;
        ; Earlier prose described this span as "dasm FF-fill" and
        ; "unreferenced"; that was wrong.  The bytes are genuine
        ; LVL_INIT_SPRITE payload that seeds the hit-entity
        ; active-flag array at cold start and on every level restart.
        DS 12,$FF
@ %def LVL_INIT_ENTITY_HIT_STATE

<<lvl init sprite tail data>>=

