\section{Perspective-floor sprite blitter}

[[INTERLACE_BLIT_P1]] and [[INTERLACE_BLIT_P2]] are the streaming-source twin of [[INTERLACE_FILL_P1]] and
[[INTERLACE_FILL_P2]]: where the FILL helpers broadcast a single byte
([[A]]) across all 105 interlaced rows of a column, the BLIT helpers
pull one source byte per relative-row from [[(ZP_BLIT_SRC),Y]] and
paint it into the same 3-band perspective layout on hi-res page~1
(respectively page~2).  The net effect is a sprite blit: a 35-row-tall
column of source bytes lands at a chosen screen column, simultaneously
echoed into rows 72--106, 112--146, and 152--186.

\subsection{Control-flow shape}

Both routines share the same outer-loop skeleton.  The caller loads a
sprite pointer into [[ZP_BLIT_SRC]] and sets
[[ZP_BLIT_X_START]] ([[$59]], the rightmost screen column, inclusive)
and [[ZP_BLIT_X_END]] ([[$58]], the left terminator --- exclusive: the
loop stops on equality without painting column [[ZP_BLIT_X_END]]).  The
routine walks X from [[ZP_BLIT_X_START]] downward, calling 35 unrolled
``paint one source byte to all three bands + INY'' groups per column.
Y is never reset between columns: the source layout is a flat,
column-major stream of 35 bytes per column, rightmost column first
(matching [[DRAW_SPRITE]]'s rightmost-first byte order within a row,
rotated 90$^{\circ}$: here each ``column'' of the sprite is 35
contiguous bytes, and columns are stacked left$\rightarrow$right in
source order).

A pre-paint guard ([[CPX #$28]]) handles the case where
[[ZP_BLIT_X_START]] starts at or past hi-res column~40: for each such
``off-screen'' iteration the paint body is skipped but Y still advances
by 35, so the source pointer stays aligned with the column counter.  In
normal use the guard never fires (callers clamp [[ZP_BLIT_X_START]]
below 40 before the JSR), but the code preserves that behaviour for
safety.

\subsection{Row pattern}

The 35 unrolled groups paint the same 105 row indices as
[[INTERLACE_FILL_P1]]: groups 0\ldots7 cover rows 72\ldots79 (band~0),
112\ldots119 (band~1), and 152\ldots159 (band~2); groups 8\ldots15
cover rows 80\ldots87 / 120\ldots127 / 160\ldots167; and so on,
finishing with group 34 at rows 106 / 146 / 186.  The three STA
operands within each group are hand-ordered to match the Apple~II
hi-res memory interleave, so the per-group 3-STA triplet lands in three
``screen holes'' of the hi-res address map.

\subsection{Callers and twin selection}

Four caller sites --- all four now carved out of the
[[<<game engine A>>]] hex blob as their own chunks --- share
the same shape:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Load a 16-bit pointer from a sprite-address table into
      [[ZP_BLIT_SRC]]/[[ZP_BLIT_SRC+1]].
\item Check [[ZP_PAGE_FLAG]] ([[BIT $00]]/[[BMI]]) to select the
      page-1 or page-2 twin, then [[JSR]] the appropriate blit
      helper.
\end{enumerate}

The four callers are:
\begin{itemize}
\item [[REFRESH_RIGHT_WALL]] --- right-edge
      playfield wall (shared tail at [[$624C]], [[INTERLACE_BLIT]] for page~1).
\item [[REFRESH_LEFT_WALL]] --- left-edge playfield
      wall (shared tail at [[$62AC]], [[INTERLACE_BLIT]] for page~2 --- the task-named site).
\item [[REFRESH_FLOOR_LINES]] --- four-row floor
      painter (no shared tail; tail-calls
      [[FLOOR_LINES_P1]]/[[FLOOR_LINES_P2]] instead of [[INTERLACE_BLIT]]).
\item [[REFRESH_PILLARS]] --- six-slot landmark
      pillar loop (shared tail at [[$62FD]], [[INTERLACE_BLIT]] for page~2).
\end{itemize}

The selectors pick [[INTERLACE_BLIT_P1]] when [[ZP_PAGE_FLAG]] is
positive and [[INTERLACE_BLIT_P2]] otherwise --- the same gating
pattern already documented for [[INTERLACE_RESTORE_P1]]/[[P2]].  The
sprite tables at [[PILLAR_SPR_LO]]/[[PILLAR_SPR_HI]], [[FLOOR_SPR_LO]]/[[FLOOR_SPR_HI]], [[WALL_L_SPR_LO]]/[[WALL_L_SPR_HI]], and [[WALL_SPR_LO]]/[[WALL_SPR_HI]] hold pointers into the swappable level banks;
the sprites have widths in the 1\,column (40 bytes) to 4\,columns
(140 bytes) range, producing the thin vertical pillar/column
decorations visible in the Drol playfield (see
Figure~\ref{fig:interlace-blit-demo}).

