\paragraph{Fast sprite-table base arithmetic.}  The stance-path
code inside [[ENEMY_A_DRAW]] writes [[LDA SPRITE_TABLE_A_BODY_LO]],X; [[STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO]]; [[LDA SPRITE_TABLE_A_BODY_HI]],X;
[[STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI]] to patch the DRAW\_SPRITE source pointer.  All four bases used by enemy-A are
\emph{one byte apart per pair}: [[$B009]]/[[$B089]] for the body, [[$B010]]/[[$B090]]
for walk-variant~1, [[$B017]]/[[$B097]] for the stance feet, [[$B01E]]/[[$B09E]]
for walk-variant~2.  Because the paired (lo,\,hi) tables are exactly
[[$80]] apart, the two [[STA]] instructions patch
[[SMC_DS_SRC_LO]] and [[SMC_DS_SRC_HI]] from a single X index.

\paragraph{Sprite art.}  Figure~\ref{fig:enemy_a_sprites} shows all
four enemy-A pointer tables laid out as 7-frame rows.  The top row
is the large body sprite [[SPRITE_TABLE_A_BODY]] ([[$04]]$\times$[[$13]]),
rendered at a smaller scale so it fits alongside the tiny
stance-feet and walk-feet tables below it.  All four tables are
indexed by [[PROJ_FRAME_IDX]] and share the same $X$ index for
paired lo/hi access.  Sprite bytes live in the level-swappable
region ([[SPRITE_TABLE_A_BODY_DATA]]..[[SPRITE_TABLE_B_DATA]]) and
