\section{Staging buffers and stack/vector page images}

The [[$5C00]]--[[$5FFF]] region is the ``staging buffers'' block
loaded from the first two sectors of track~1.  It sits inside the
game-code address space but serves two distinct roles:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{One-shot install source} --- on cold boot, [[FIRST_BOOT]]
  copies 240 bytes from [[STAGE_STACK]] ([[$5C00]]) into [[STACK_PAGE]]
  ([[$0100]]) and another 240 bytes from [[STAGE_VECTORS]] ([[$5D00]])
  into [[VECTOR_PAGE]] ([[$0300]]).  This seeds the stack page with
  [[SCREEN_ROW_COPY]], [[JOYSTICK_HANDLER]], [[KEY_HANDLER_EXT]], and
  [[ROW_COPY_CLICK]]; and the vector page with [[TEXT_STRIP_SRC]]
  plus various small data tables.  After the copy, the original
  bytes at [[STAGE_STACK]] and [[STAGE_VECTORS]] are no longer
  referenced by the FIRST\_BOOT path.
\item \textbf{Stable screen-wipe callback} --- the loader's
  [[SCREEN_PRE_RESTORE]] (at loader.bin offset [[$58A0]] before
  relocation, live at [[SCREEN_PRE_RESTORE]] after it) calls [[JSR]]
  [[STAGE_STACK]]
  before restoring the hi-res display.  Because the [[$0100]] stack
  page gets overwritten by 6502 stack operations during normal play,
  the [[STAGE_STACK]] copy of [[SCREEN_ROW_COPY]] is the
  only reliably-intact entry point for the wipe animation at the
  moment the loader wants to repaint.  Only the first 43 bytes
  ([[$5C00]]--[[$5C2A]]) are live at runtime; the remaining
  [[$5C2B]]--[[$5CFF]] tail is dead residue of the install-time image.
\end{itemize}

The [[$5E00]]--[[$5EC4]] block following the two page images is
[[STAGE_RESIDUE_DEAD]]: a 197-byte dead fragment that opens with a
Disk II nibble-level sector reader ([[STAGE_DISK_MOTOR_ON]],
[[STAGE_DISK_DATA]], [[DISK_Q6_OFF]]/[[DISK_Q6_ON]]/[[DISK_Q7_OFF]]
soft switches), runs through a seven-step retry delay that mistakenly
targets [[DEAD_BA00_OVL]] (sprite data at run time, not code), calls
into [[NIBBLE_READER_OVL]] (a mid-instruction entry into the live
[[NIBBLE_READER]]), and finally drops into a
[[GAME_START_INIT]]-style tail that re-zeros the BCD score digits,
reseeds [[HUD_SCORE_COL]]/[[HUD_LIVES_COL]] and [[ZP_PLAYER_Y]],
calls [[INIT_LEVEL_STATE]], and falls through into
[[RESTART_DISPATCH]] (itself statically dead).  The restart tail
carries a small [[BIT]]-abs 3-byte NOP trick on its [[STA ZP_SCORE_1]]
operand that lets a mid-block branch (taken from the
[[NIBBLE_READER_OVL]] return) skip the third-digit zero and land
directly on the HUD seed.  Nothing in any shipped binary jumps into
any of this --- linear disassembly of [[drol.bin]] finds no
[[JSR]]/[[JMP]] targeting any address in [[$5C2B]]--[[$5FFF]] other
than the live [[STAGE_STACK]] entry.  The bytes are preserved
verbatim for byte-exactness but serve no runtime purpose.

\paragraph{The [[$5ED4]]--[[$5FFF]] tail: pre-release twin of
[[$BED4]]--[[$BFFF]].}  The remaining 300-byte chunk is the single
most revealing piece of dead residue in the staging area.  It
partitions into three sub-blocks:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[$5ED4]]--[[$5EFF]] (44 bytes, [[STAGE_DEAD_RELOAD]]): two
  small RWTS-retry helpers that call into the [[$BE95]] /
  [[$BE5A]] / [[$BDBC]] rwts entry points and fall through into the
  reset-handler body below.  These 44 bytes have no counterpart in
  the live [[rwts.bin]] --- they are unique to this dead region.
\item [[$5F00]]--[[$5F47]] (72 bytes, [[STAGE_DEAD_RESET]]): an
  almost-exact copy of the reset-handler common body at
  [[$BF00]]--[[$BF47]] ([[RESET_R]]/[[RESET_P]]/[[RESET_L]]/[[RESET_BANG]]
  minus their [[BIT]]-abs selector prefix).  A single byte differs:
  the clear-memory pointer is initialised to [[$BE00]] here, whereas
  the live reset handler at [[$BF00]] starts one page lower at
  [[$BD00]].  Later in development somebody shifted the clear-memory
  top by one page to avoid stepping on newly-added game data, but
  neglected to update this twin copy.
\item [[$5F48]]--[[$5FFF]] (184 bytes): an exact byte-for-byte
  duplicate of [[$BF48]]--[[$BFFF]] --- the trailing
  [[LDR_TRACK]]/[[LDR_SLOT]]/[[LDR_PHASE]] slot, the
  [[SCROLL_UP_PRE]]/[[SCROLL_DN]] pair, and the 64-byte
  [[SCREEN_ADDR_TBL]] --- with one caveat: the scroll routines here
  still index [[SCREEN_ADDR_TBL]] (the post-relocation
  address), not at [[$5FC0]] (this copy), so even if their [[$5F4B]]
  and [[$5F7F]] entry points were called they would reach into the
  live language-card table anyway.  This strongly suggests that the
  original loader plan was to copy [[$5E00]]--[[$5FFF]] into
  [[$BE00]]--[[$BFFF]] via [[COPY_ROM_TO_LC]], matching the shape of
  the other relocations in the boot chain.  The plan was dropped
  (the live [[rwts.bin]] is assembled directly at [[$BE00]] and copied
  into place by the loader's dedicated copy step), but the staging
  bytes were left behind --- verbatim for [[$5F48]]--[[$5FFF]], with
  one stale page byte at [[$5F21]] for the reset handler.
\end{itemize}

No shipped binary jumps into any address in [[$5ED4]]--[[$5FFF]];
confirmed by linear disassembly of all four targets.  The bytes are
preserved for byte-exact matching against [[drol.bin]].

