<<draw player defines>>=

; --- Zero-page (player sprite renderer) ---
ZP_ACTION_DIR   = $02           ; Action flag: $00=idle, $01=ascend, $FF=descend
ZP_PLAYER_STANCE = $03          ; Player stance / floor index (clamped $03..$09)
; ZP_PLAYER_COL, ZP_HIT_FLAG, $FD (frame counter) are defined elsewhere.

; --- Main-player sprite pointer tables (indexed by ZP_PLAYER_STANCE) ---

; --- Pseudo-random static source inside DRAW_PLAYER's own code image ---
; Used for the teleport/flicker effect at the top and bottom floors.
; The two tables overlap the routine itself ($6500-$66FF), so no data
; fixture is needed.
PLAYER_STATIC_LO = $6500        ; Low byte of flicker sprite pointer (by ZP_FRAME_COUNTER)
PLAYER_STATIC_HI = $6600        ; High byte (ANDed with $7F) of flicker pointer

; --- Self-modifying operand aliases inside DRAW_PLAYER ---
; Both bytes are patched by LEVEL_INTRO_TICK (intro countdown, fading)
; and LEVEL_COMPLETE (restore defaults after the transition animation).
SMC_SR_HEIGHT   = $64F6         ; Immediate operand of "LDA #$13" --- sprite height
SMC_SR_YSRC     = $64FA         ; ZP operand of "LDA $06" --- sprite Y source

@

<<draw player>>=

        ORG $64DF
DRAW_PLAYER:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Main-loop player sprite renderer (called from MAIN_LOOP's
        ; JSR SPRITE_RENDER slot, SMC-toggled $20/$2C).  Draws
        ; the big centre-screen player sprite at column $14.  Two code
        ; paths, selected by the action flag ZP_ACTION_DIR:
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_ACTION_DIR       --- $00 idle, $01 ascend, $FF descend.
        ;   ZP_PLAYER_STANCE    --- stance/floor index ($03..$09);
        ;                                 $03 = top floor, $09 = bottom floor.
        ;   ZP_PLAYER_COL       --- sprite Y row (via SMC_SR_YSRC).
        ;   ZP_HIT_FLAG         --- $00 intro / $80..$FF hit: skip
        ;                                 the action-path flicker draw.
        ;   $FD                       --- frame counter, indexes the
        ;                                 flicker's pseudo-random static source.
        ;   PLAYER_SPR_IDLE_LO/HI     --- idle sprite pointers.
        ;   PLAYER_SPR_ACTIVE_LO/HI   --- active sprite pointers.
        ;   SMC_SR_HEIGHT     --- live height immediate (may be
        ;                                 shrunk by LEVEL_INTRO_TICK).
        ;   SMC_SR_YSRC       --- live ZP source for sprite Y
        ;                                 (normally $06 = ZP_PLAYER_COL,
        ;                                 $17 = ZP_INTRO_Y during intro).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Idle ($02 == 0): pick sprite from PLAYER_SPR_IDLE tables,
        ;     width $03, height (SMC_SR_HEIGHT, default $13), Y from
        ;     (SMC_SR_YSRC, default ZP_PLAYER_COL), X column $14, then
        ;     JSR DRAW_SPRITE; RTS.
        ;   Active ($02 != 0): if $1E > 0 and the stance is $03 or $09,
        ;     first draw a $00 x $06 teleport-flicker sprite using
        ;     bytes of this routine's own code image as static, masked
        ;     by AND #$83 or AND #$B0 via the live SMC slot
        ;     SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP/ARG inside DRAW_SPRITE.  Then draw the
        ;     main body from PLAYER_SPR_ACTIVE tables at width ZP_PLAYER_STANCE,
        ;     height $14, falling through into the idle path's
        ;     column/Y-source/JSR.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   SMC_DS_SRC_LO/HI,
        ;   SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP/ARG,
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_W/H, ZP_SPRITE_Y/X,
        ;   hi-res page framebuffer.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

; --- Gate on action flag ---
        LDA ZP_ACTION_DIR
        BNE .action_path                ;   non-zero = elevator in motion

; --- Idle path: single body sprite from PLAYER_SPR_IDLE tables ---
.idle_path:
        LDX ZP_PLAYER_STANCE
        LDA PLAYER_SPR_IDLE_LO,X        ; Sprite pointer low byte
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA PLAYER_SPR_IDLE_HI,X        ; Sprite pointer high byte
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        LDA #$03
        STA ZP_SPRITE_W                 ; Width = 3 bytes
        LDA #$13                        ; Default height = $13
                                        ; (#$13 byte at SMC_SR_HEIGHT=$64F6,
                                        ;  patched by LEVEL_INTRO_TICK)
        STA ZP_SPRITE_H
.share_tail:
        LDA ZP_PLAYER_COL               ; Y source = $06 (at SMC_SR_YSRC=$64FA,
                                        ; patched to ZP_INTRO_Y=ZP_INTRO_Y by
                                        ; LEVEL_INTRO_TICK during intro)
        STA ZP_SPRITE_Y
        LDA #$14
        STA ZP_SPRITE_X                 ; X column = $14 (screen centre)
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        RTS

; --- Action path: optional flicker + main body ---
.action_path:
        LDA ZP_HIT_FLAG
        BMI .body_from_active           ;   hit: body only, no flicker
        BEQ .body_from_active           ;   intro: body only, no flicker

; --- Check stance against floor-extreme values $03 / $09 ---
        LDA ZP_PLAYER_STANCE
        CMP #$03                        ; Top floor?
        BNE .check_bottom
        LDA #$14                        ; Flicker X column = $14 (top)
        STA ZP_SPRITE_X
        LDA #$83                        ; Flicker mask = AND #$83
        STA SMC_SPRITE_MASK_ARG
        JMP .flicker_setup
.check_bottom:
        CMP #$09                        ; Bottom floor?
        BNE .body_from_active           ;   neither: skip flicker
        LDA #$11                        ; Flicker X column = $11 (bottom)
        STA ZP_SPRITE_X
        LDA #$B0                        ; Flicker mask = AND #$B0
        STA SMC_SPRITE_MASK_ARG

; --- Flicker draw: static from code image, masked by AND imm ---
.flicker_setup:
        LDA #$29                        ; $29 = AND #imm opcode
        STA SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP          ;   patch live SMC slot in DRAW_SPRITE
        LDA ZP_PLAYER_COL
        CLC
        ADC #$0D                        ;   + $0D
        STA ZP_SPRITE_Y                 ; Y = player_col + $0D
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_SPRITE_W                 ; Width = 0+1 byte
        LDA #$06
        STA ZP_SPRITE_H                 ; Height = 6 rows
        LDY ZP_FRAME_COUNTER            ; Frame counter
        LDA PLAYER_STATIC_LO,Y          ; Pseudo-random low from own code
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA PLAYER_STATIC_HI,Y          ; Pseudo-random high ...
        AND #$7F                        ;   masked into INPUT_DISPATCH-$66FF range
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        LDA #$24                        ; $24 = BIT zp opcode (2-byte NOP)
        STA SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP          ;   restore normal draw path

; --- Main body draw from PLAYER_SPR_ACTIVE tables ---
.body_from_active:
        LDX ZP_PLAYER_STANCE
        LDA PLAYER_SPR_ACTIVE_LO,X      ; Pointer low
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA PLAYER_SPR_ACTIVE_HI,X      ; Pointer high
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        LDA #$03
        STA ZP_SPRITE_W                 ; Width = 3 bytes
        LDA #$14
        STA ZP_SPRITE_H                 ; Height = $14 (one taller than idle)
        JMP .share_tail                 ; Share idle-path tail at $64F9:
                                        ;   loads ZP_PLAYER_COL, sets
                                        ;   X=$14, JSR DRAW_SPRITE, RTS.
@ %def DRAW_PLAYER
@ %def PLAYER_STATIC_LO PLAYER_STATIC_HI
@ %def SMC_SR_HEIGHT SMC_SR_YSRC ZP_ACTION_DIR ZP_PLAYER_STANCE

\section{Sprite draw (transparent blit)}

[[DRAW_SPRITE]] is the game's main sprite draw routine --- it
is called from about 40 places (projectiles, entities, UI sprites, the
attract logo, extra-life animation). It OR-blits a rectangular sprite
onto the currently-hidden hi-res page, using
[[ZP_PAGE_FLAG]] (bit~7) to choose between page~1 (addresses
[[$2000]]--[[$3FFF]], row-high table [[SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI]]) and
page~2 (addresses [[$4000]]--[[$5FFF]], row-high table
[[SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2]]).  Row-low bytes always come from
[[SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_LO]].

Inputs are the usual sprite-parameter quartet:
\begin{itemize}
\item [[ZP_SPRITE_W]] --- width in bytes.
\item [[ZP_SPRITE_H]] --- height in rows.
\item [[ZP_SPRITE_Y]] --- starting screen row.
\item [[ZP_SPRITE_X]] --- starting column (right edge).
\item [[SPRITE_PTR_LO]]/[[SPRITE_PTR_HI]] ([[$65B3]]/[[$65B4]],
  self-modifying operand bytes of the sprite-data fetch) --- source
  pointer into sprite data.
\end{itemize}

The routine is heavily self-modifying. On entry it patches three
absolute-address operands with the current screen row address:
\begin{itemize}
\item The [[LDA xxxx,X]] early in [[DRAW_SPRITE]] selects the row-high-byte table
  ([[SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI]] or~[[SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2]]), based on [[ZP_PAGE_FLAG]].
\item The [[ORA xxxx,X]] and [[STA xxxx,X]] inside the inner loop both
  get patched with the current row's base screen address on every
  outer-loop iteration.
\end{itemize}

The outer loop (one iteration per row) walks the sprite data byte-by-byte
using Y. The inner loop walks X from the right edge of the sprite
toward the left, decrementing the byte counter in ZP~[[$5A]]. For each
byte: if the destination column is out of range ([[X >= $28]]), the
sprite byte is skipped but Y is still advanced. Otherwise the sprite
byte is fetched; if it is zero the source byte is skipped (transparency);
otherwise the byte is OR'd into the screen memory at the row/column
position.

\paragraph{Live flicker slot at [[SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP]] / [[SMC_SPRITE_MASK_ARG]].}  Immediately before
the inner-loop [[ORA]] instruction there are two bytes --- [[$24 $00]]
--- that on the disk image encode [[BIT $00]] and act as a 2-byte NOP
in the normal draw path.  This is \emph{not} dead padding: at runtime
[[LEVEL_INTRO_TICK]] patches these two bytes to [[AND
\#<flicker>]] ([[$29 <imm>]]) for every frame of the intro countdown so
that the sprite byte is AND-masked against the low bit of the frame
counter before being OR'd into the screen.  This makes the intro
sprite flash on every other frame without needing a separate draw
routine.  After each intro draw the two bytes are restored to [[$24
$00]] so the regular draw path sees a 2-byte NOP again.  The two slots
are labelled [[SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP]] (opcode byte) and
[[SMC_SPRITE_MASK_ARG]] (operand byte) and are declared in the
level-intro defines chunk.

There is a short dead-code tail inside [[DRAW_SPRITE]] that is only reachable
from an unreachable [[CPX #$00 / BCS]] fall-through earlier in the routine
(the [[BCS]] is always taken because X is unsigned). The bytes are kept
verbatim so that the binary stays byte-perfect.

<<draw sprite defines>>=

; --- Zero-page (sprite draw parameters) ---
ZP_SPRITE_W     = $56           ; Sprite width (bytes per row)
ZP_SPRITE_H     = $57           ; Sprite height (rows)
ZP_SPRITE_ROW_REMAIN = $5A      ; Inner-loop byte-countdown scratch
ZP_SPRITE_Y     = $5B           ; Sprite starting screen row
ZP_SPRITE_X     = $5D           ; Sprite starting column (right edge)

; --- Self-mod operand placeholder ---
; Disk-image value for the four self-modifying absolute operands in
; DRAW_SPRITE.  $9000 is outside the game's memory map and serves only
; as a harmless initial pattern; all four are overwritten before the
; instructions are executed.
SPRITE_SMC_INIT = $9000
@

<<draw sprite>>=

        ORG $656F
DRAW_SPRITE:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Sprite draw --- transparent (OR) blit to the hidden hi-res page.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_W      --- width in bytes per row
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_H      --- height in rows
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_Y      --- starting screen row (0..191)
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_X      --- starting column (right edge)
        ;   SPRITE_PTR_LO/HI       --- source pointer (self-mod operand of
        ;                              the LDA abs,Y at $65B2)
        ;   ZP_PAGE_FLAG b7  --- selects page 1 (clear) or page 2
        ;                              (set) as the draw target.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Patches its own row-address-table operand based on
        ;   ZP_PAGE_FLAG.  Outer loop (ZP_SPRITE_H iterations) walks
        ;   rows; for each row it refreshes the ORA/STA operands with
        ;   the row's base screen address.  Inner loop walks
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_W bytes from the right edge leftward: columns
        ;   off the right edge and zero source bytes are transparent,
        ;   otherwise the byte is OR'd into screen RAM.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   Self (operands, $65BA/$65BB, $65BD/$65BE),
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_ROW_REMAIN, ZP_SPRITE_Y (post-increment).
        ;
        ; Note: the [[BIT $00]] ([[SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP]] /
        ; [[SMC_SPRITE_MASK_ARG]]) is a *live* self-modifying slot --- it
        ; acts as a 2-byte NOP during normal draws, but LEVEL_INTRO_TICK
        ; patches it to [[AND #<flicker>]] for each countdown frame to
        ; flash the intro sprite on every other frame.  It is restored
        ; before this routine is entered by non-intro callers.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

; --- Select row-high table based on ZP_PAGE_FLAG ---
        BIT ZP_PAGE_FLAG
        BMI .page2
        LDA #<SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI  ; $C0 --- low of SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI (page 1)
        STA SMC_ROW_HI_LO
        LDA #>SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI
        STA SMC_ROW_HI_HI
        JMP .outer_entry
.page2:
        LDA #<SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2 ; $40 --- low of SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2 (page 2)
        STA SMC_ROW_HI_LO
        LDA #>SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2 ; $74
        STA SMC_ROW_HI_HI

; --- Entry into the draw loop: initialise sprite-data index ---
.outer_entry:
        LDY #$00

; --- Outer loop: one iteration per sprite row ---
.next_row:
        LDA ZP_SPRITE_W
        STA ZP_SPRITE_ROW_REMAIN  ; Inner-loop byte counter
        LDX ZP_SPRITE_Y           ; Current screen row (0..191)
SMC_ROW_HI_LO = *+1               ; Low of LDA abs,X operand --- patched
SMC_ROW_HI_HI = *+2               ; High of LDA abs,X operand --- patched
        LDA SPRITE_SMC_INIT,X     ; runtime: LDA SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI,X or LDA SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2,X
        STA SMC_ORA_HI            ; Patch ORA operand (high byte)
        STA SMC_STA_HI            ; Patch STA operand (high byte)
        LDA SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_LO,X  ; Row-low (fixed SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_LO table)
        STA SMC_ORA_LO            ; Patch ORA operand (low byte)
        STA SMC_STA_LO            ; Patch STA operand (low byte)

; --- Inner loop: one iteration per sprite byte on this row ---
        LDX ZP_SPRITE_X           ; Destination column
.col_loop:
        CPX #$28                  ; Column >= 40 (off right edge)?
        BCS .col_skip             ;   yes --- transparent
        CPX #$00                  ; (Dead: X unsigned, BCS always taken)
        BCS .fetch_src
        INY                       ; (unreachable) advance and skip
        JMP .dead_tail            ; (unreachable) jump to dead tail
.fetch_src:
SPRITE_PTR_LO = *+1               ; Low of LDA abs,Y operand --- caller sets
SPRITE_PTR_HI = *+2               ; High of LDA abs,Y operand --- caller sets
        LDA SPRITE_SMC_INIT,Y     ; Runtime: LDA (sprite_ptr),Y
        BEQ .col_skip             ; Zero pixel --- transparent
; SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP / SMC_SPRITE_MASK_ARG: live SMC slot.
; Disk-image bytes $24 $00 encode BIT $00, which is a 2-byte NOP for
; normal callers.  LEVEL_INTRO_TICK patches to AND #imm for intro
; flicker frames, then restores $24 $00 before returning.
SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP  = *           ; SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP--- opcode byte (BIT zp / AND imm)
SMC_SPRITE_MASK_ARG = *+1         ; SMC_SPRITE_MASK_ARG--- operand byte (ZP addr / AND imm)
        DC.B $24, $00             ; BIT $00 --- flicker-mask SMC slot
SMC_ORA_LO = *+1                  ; Low of ORA abs,X operand --- patched
SMC_ORA_HI = *+2                  ; High of ORA abs,X operand --- patched
        ORA SPRITE_SMC_INIT,X     ; OR with screen byte (SMC operand)
SMC_STA_LO = *+1                  ; Low of STA abs,X operand --- patched
SMC_STA_HI = *+2                  ; High of STA abs,X operand --- patched
        STA SPRITE_SMC_INIT,X     ; Store back (SMC operand)
.col_skip:
        INY                       ; Next sprite byte
        DEX                       ; Move left one column
        DEC ZP_SPRITE_ROW_REMAIN
        BPL .col_loop             ; More bytes on this row?

; --- Advance to next row ---
.advance_row:                     ; -- BMI target from dead tail
        INC ZP_SPRITE_Y           ; Next screen row
        DEC ZP_SPRITE_H           ; Rows remaining?
        BNE .next_row
        RTS

; --- Dead-code tail ($65CC-$65D4, 9 bytes) ---
; Reached only from the unreachable "INY / JMP" at $65AE-$65B1
; (since [[CPX #$00 / BCS]] is always taken).  Retained verbatim
; for byte-faithful assembly.
.dead_tail:
        DEX
        DEC ZP_SPRITE_ROW_REMAIN
        BMI .advance_row          ; -- target $65C5
        INY
        JMP .dead_tail
@ %def DRAW_SPRITE SPRITE_PTR_LO SPRITE_PTR_HI

\section{Sprite draw (playfield, HUD-clipped)}

[[DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD]] is a sibling of [[DRAW_SPRITE]] that performs an identical transparent OR-blit onto the
hidden hi-res page, but with a \emph{narrower} column-acceptance
window.  It is called only from [[DRAW_ENTITIES]] --- its four sites
draw the player, the ``special'' sprite, the two companion slots and
the 20-slot entity list --- so every gameplay sprite that moves over
the playfield goes through this routine rather than through
[[DRAW_SPRITE]].

The two routines share almost every byte: the same row-high-table
selection based on [[ZP_PAGE_FLAG]], the same outer row loop, the
same self-modifying [[ORA]]/[[STA]] operands on the inner write, the
same sprite-parameter quartet
([[ZP_SPRITE_W]]/[[ZP_SPRITE_H]]/[[ZP_SPRITE_Y]]/[[ZP_SPRITE_X]]).  They
differ only in the inner-loop column check and in what tail code they
carry.

\paragraph{Column clip window.}  Where [[DRAW_SPRITE]] accepts every
column $0 \le X < 40$ (reject $X \ge [[$28]]$), this routine rejects
\emph{three} sets of columns:

\begin{itemize}
\item $X = [[$0B]]$ --- the left playfield wall column.  A
  [[CPX #$0B / BEQ]] explicitly singles it out.
\item $X \ge [[$1C]]$ --- any column to the right of the playfield.
  Columns [[$1C]]--[[$27]] are the right-hand HUD strip (the HISCORE panel
  and digits); the implicit wrap also covers columns $\ge [[$28]]$ (off
  the right edge of the screen).
\item Zero source byte --- same transparency rule as [[DRAW_SPRITE]].
\end{itemize}

The accepted window is therefore cols [[$00]]--[[$0A]] and [[$0C]]--[[$1B]]
(27~columns), which is exactly the gameplay region of the screen.
See the HUD frame image: the [[SCORE]] panel (cols [[$00]]--[[$09]]) is
\emph{inside} the accepted window --- so score digits drawn through
regular HUD code land there, but gameplay sprites momentarily passing
through the same columns will also draw on top of the score panel.
Only col~[[$0B]] (the left vertical wall of the top playfield strip) and
the entire right HISCORE region are protected.

\paragraph{No flicker SMC slot.}  [[DRAW_SPRITE]] has a live
self-modifying [[BIT $00]] slot at [[SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP]] (patched to [[AND \#imm]]
by [[LEVEL_INTRO_TICK]] for intro flicker frames).  This routine does
\emph{not} --- the inner OR is unconditional.  The intro flicker
mechanism only applies to the intro sprite drawn via [[DRAW_SPRITE]]
from [[LEVEL_INTRO_TICK]], not to playfield entities.

\paragraph{No dead tail.}  [[DRAW_SPRITE]] has an unreachable 9-byte
[[INY / JMP]] tail left over from an earlier draft.
[[DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD]] has no such tail --- it is 87~bytes of live code.

\paragraph{Source-pointer SMC.}  The [[LDA $9000,Y]] inside [[DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD]]'s inner loop is
patched by [[DRAW_ENTITIES]] with the per-sprite source-data address
before each call.  The operand bytes are named [[SMC_PFB_SRC_LO]] and [[SMC_PFB_SRC_HI]], exported for the callers.
Disk-image initial value is [[$9000]] --- a harmless pattern outside the
game's memory map, overwritten before the first execution.

<<draw sprite playfield>>=

        ORG $65D5
DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Transparent (OR) blit with HUD-column clipping.
        ; Sibling of DRAW_SPRITE: identical structure, but the
        ; inner column check rejects col $0B (left playfield wall) and
        ; cols >=$1C (right HISCORE HUD panel + offscreen) instead of
        ; the simple >=$28 offscreen check.  There is no flicker SMC
        ; slot and no dead-code tail.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_W      --- width in bytes per row
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_H      --- height in rows
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_Y      --- starting screen row (0..191)
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_X      --- starting column (right edge)
        ;   SMC_PFB_SRC_LO/HI      --- source pointer (self-mod operand
        ;                              of the LDA abs,Y at $6614),
        ;                              patched by DRAW_ENTITIES.
        ;   ZP_PAGE_FLAG b7  --- selects page 1 (clear) or page 2
        ;                              (set) as the draw target.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Outer loop walks ZP_SPRITE_H rows.  For each row, patches
        ;   the ORA/STA operands with the row's base screen address
        ;   (high byte from SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI or SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2 via the row-high SMC operand,
        ;   low byte from SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_LO).  Inner loop walks
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_W bytes from the right edge leftward: rejects
        ;   col $0B, rejects cols >=$1C, rejects zero source bytes;
        ;   otherwise OR's the sprite byte into screen RAM.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   Self (operands at SMC_PFB_ROW_HI_LO/HI, SMC_PFB_ORA_LO/HI,
        ;   SMC_PFB_STA_LO/HI), ZP_SPRITE_ROW_REMAIN,
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_Y (post-increment).
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

; --- Select row-high table based on ZP_PAGE_FLAG ---
        BIT ZP_PAGE_FLAG
        BMI .page2
        LDA #<SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI  ; $C0 --- low of SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI (page 1)
        STA SMC_PFB_ROW_HI_LO
        LDA #>SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI
        STA SMC_PFB_ROW_HI_HI
        JMP .outer_entry
.page2:
        LDA #<SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2 ; $40 --- low of SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2 (page 2)
        STA SMC_PFB_ROW_HI_LO
        LDA #>SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2 ; $74
        STA SMC_PFB_ROW_HI_HI

; --- Entry into the draw loop: initialise sprite-data index ---
.outer_entry:
        LDY #$00

; --- Outer loop: one iteration per sprite row ---
.next_row:
        LDA ZP_SPRITE_W
        STA ZP_SPRITE_ROW_REMAIN  ; Inner-loop byte counter
        LDX ZP_SPRITE_Y           ; Current screen row (0..191)
SMC_PFB_ROW_HI_LO = *+1           ; Low of LDA abs,X operand --- patched
SMC_PFB_ROW_HI_HI = *+2           ; High of LDA abs,X operand --- patched
        LDA SPRITE_SMC_INIT,X     ; runtime: LDA SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI,X or LDA SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2,X
        STA SMC_PFB_ORA_HI        ; Patch ORA operand (high byte)
        STA SMC_PFB_STA_HI        ; Patch STA operand (high byte)
        LDA SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_LO,X  ; Row-low (fixed SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_LO table)
        STA SMC_PFB_ORA_LO        ; Patch ORA operand (low byte)
        STA SMC_PFB_STA_LO        ; Patch STA operand (low byte)

; --- Inner loop: one iteration per sprite byte on this row ---
        LDX ZP_SPRITE_X           ; Destination column
.col_loop:
        CPX #$0B                  ; Left playfield wall column?
        BEQ .col_skip             ;   yes --- transparent
        CPX #$1C                  ; HISCORE HUD panel or offscreen right?
        BCS .col_skip             ;   yes --- transparent
SMC_PFB_SRC_LO = *+1              ; Low of LDA abs,Y operand --- caller sets
SMC_PFB_SRC_HI = *+2              ; High of LDA abs,Y operand --- caller sets
        LDA SPRITE_SMC_INIT,Y     ; Runtime: LDA (sprite_ptr),Y
        BEQ .col_skip             ; Zero pixel --- transparent
SMC_PFB_ORA_LO = *+1              ; Low of ORA abs,X operand --- patched
SMC_PFB_ORA_HI = *+2              ; High of ORA abs,X operand --- patched
        ORA SPRITE_SMC_INIT,X     ; OR with screen byte (SMC operand)
SMC_PFB_STA_LO = *+1              ; Low of STA abs,X operand --- patched
SMC_PFB_STA_HI = *+2              ; High of STA abs,X operand --- patched
        STA SPRITE_SMC_INIT,X     ; Store back (SMC operand)
.col_skip:
        INY                       ; Next sprite byte
        DEX                       ; Move left one column
        DEC ZP_SPRITE_ROW_REMAIN
        BPL .col_loop             ; More bytes on this row?

; --- Advance to next row ---
        INC ZP_SPRITE_Y           ; Next screen row
        DEC ZP_SPRITE_H           ; Rows remaining?
        BNE .next_row
        RTS
@ %def DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD SMC_PFB_SRC_LO SMC_PFB_SRC_HI

\section{Sprite draw (opaque)}

[[DRAW_SPRITE_OPAQUE]] is the third member of Drol's
sprite-blitter triplet --- sibling of [[DRAW_SPRITE]] and
[[DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD]].  Where the other two use an
[[ORA]]/[[STA]] pair to \emph{overlay} the sprite on top of whatever
is already on the hi-res page (transparent blit), this routine uses a
plain [[STA]] that \emph{overwrites} the screen byte unconditionally
(opaque blit).  Every source byte is written, including zero bytes ---
there is no source-transparency test.

The routine shares the same sprite-parameter quartet
([[ZP_SPRITE_W]]/[[ZP_SPRITE_H]]/[[ZP_SPRITE_Y]]/[[ZP_SPRITE_X]]) and
the same [[ZP_PAGE_FLAG]]-driven row-high-table selection, so all
three blitters are drop-in compatible from the caller's point of
view.  They differ only in (1) the inner column-clip check, (2)
whether a zero source byte is skipped, and (3) whether an [[ORA]]
is performed before the [[STA]]:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\hline
                              & [[DRAW_SPRITE]]  & [[DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD]] & [[DRAW_SPRITE_OPAQUE]] \\ \hline
Reject col $\ge [[$28]]$         & yes              & implicit (via $\ge[[$1C]]$)  & yes \\
Reject col $=[[$0B]]$            & no               & yes                       & no \\
Reject col $\ge [[$1C]]$         & no               & yes                       & no \\
Skip zero source byte         & yes              & yes                       & \textbf{no} \\
OR with screen before store   & yes              & yes                       & \textbf{no} \\
Flicker SMC slot              & yes ([[$65B7]])     & no                        & no \\
Dead-code tail                & yes (9 bytes)    & no                        & no \\
Live size                     & 102 bytes        & 87 bytes                  & 72 bytes \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\paragraph{Callers.}  Three routines call [[DRAW_SPRITE_OPAQUE]]:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[DISPLAY_UPDATE]] --- draws the timer animation tile
  at column~[[$09]], row~[[$16]] (a 1$\times$6 sprite in the SCORE HUD
  strip).  Source comes from [[TIMER_FRAME_LO]]/[[TIMER_FRAME_HI]].
\item [[DRAW_DIGIT]] --- draws a single BCD digit tile
  (1$\times$6) at a caller-chosen column.  Source comes from
  [[DIGIT_TILE_LO]]/[[DIGIT_TILE_HI]].
  [[POST_FRAME]] calls this seven times per frame --- five
  score nibbles plus two level-state digits.
\item [[REFRESH_HIT_ENTITIES]] --- draws each currently-active hit-entity
  (7$\times$5 sprite) onto the freshly-cleared draw page during the
  game-engine-A per-frame tick.  Source comes from the level-data
  [[HIT_SPR_POS_LO]]/[[HI]] or [[HIT_SPR_NEG_LO]]/[[HI]] pair,
  indexed by [[ZP_SPRITE_XREF]].
\end{itemize}

The HUD callers ([[DISPLAY_UPDATE]] and [[DRAW_DIGIT]]) draw at fixed
positions where whatever was on screen previously (the previous digit,
or the previous timer frame) must be completely replaced.  An OR blit
would leave the old digit's pixels visible underneath the new one,
turning a ``0'' drawn over ``8'' into an ``8''.  The opaque STA blit
solves this by unconditionally overwriting --- which also means the
caller is responsible for clearing any region the new sprite does not
cover (the digit and timer tiles are designed as rectangular 1$\times$6
bounding boxes that tile cleanly).  [[REFRESH_HIT_ENTITIES]] relies on
the same opaque behaviour but for a different reason: its draw page
was just zeroed by [[CLEAR_DRAW_PAGE]], so there is nothing underneath
to preserve, and ORA would only add a cost it cannot benefit from.

\paragraph{Source-pointer SMC.}  The [[LDA $9000,Y]] inside [[DRAW_SPRITE_OPAQUE]] is
patched by the callers with the per-tile source-data address.  The
operand bytes are named [[SMC_TILE_SRC_LO]] and
[[SMC_TILE_SRC_HI]], exported for the callers.  Disk-image
initial value is [[$9000]] --- a harmless pattern outside the game's
memory map, overwritten before the first execution.

<<draw sprite opaque>>=

        ORG $662C
DRAW_SPRITE_OPAQUE:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Opaque (STA) blit to the hidden hi-res page.
        ; Third member of the sprite-blitter triplet --- sibling of
        ; DRAW_SPRITE ($656F, OR + source-zero skip) and
        ; DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD ($65D5, OR + source-zero skip + HUD
        ; column clip).  Unlike those two, this routine has NO
        ; source-zero transparency test and NO ORA step: every source
        ; byte is stored unconditionally, overwriting whatever was on
        ; the screen.  Column clip is the simple >=$28 offscreen
        ; check, same as DRAW_SPRITE.  Used for HUD tiles (timer
        ; animation, score/hiscore/level digits) where the previous
        ; frame's pixels must be replaced, not OR'd on top of.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_W      --- width in bytes per row
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_H      --- height in rows
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_Y      --- starting screen row (0..191)
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_X      --- starting column (right edge)
        ;   SMC_TILE_SRC_LO/HI     --- source pointer (self-mod operand
        ;                              of the LDA abs,Y at $6661),
        ;                              patched by each caller.
        ;   ZP_PAGE_FLAG b7  --- selects page 1 (clear) or page 2
        ;                              (set) as the draw target.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Outer loop walks ZP_SPRITE_H rows.  For each row, patches
        ;   the STA operand with the row's base screen address (high
        ;   byte from SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI or SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2 via the row-high SMC operand, low
        ;   byte from SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_LO).  Inner loop walks
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_W bytes from the right edge leftward: rejects
        ;   cols >=$28 (offscreen), otherwise unconditionally STA's
        ;   the source byte to screen RAM.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   Self (operands at SMC_OPQ_ROW_HI_LO/HI,
        ;   SMC_TILE_SRC_LO/HI, SMC_OPQ_STA_LO/HI),
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_ROW_REMAIN, ZP_SPRITE_Y (post-increment).
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

; --- Select row-high table based on ZP_PAGE_FLAG ---
        BIT ZP_PAGE_FLAG
        BMI .page2
        LDA #<SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI  ; $C0 --- low of SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI (page 1)
        STA SMC_OPQ_ROW_HI_LO
        LDA #>SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI
        STA SMC_OPQ_ROW_HI_HI
        JMP .outer_entry
.page2:
        LDA #<SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2 ; $40 --- low of SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2 (page 2)
        STA SMC_OPQ_ROW_HI_LO
        LDA #>SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2 ; $74
        STA SMC_OPQ_ROW_HI_HI

; --- Entry into the draw loop: initialise sprite-data index ---
.outer_entry:
        LDY #$00

; --- Outer loop: one iteration per sprite row ---
.next_row:
        LDA ZP_SPRITE_W
        STA ZP_SPRITE_ROW_REMAIN  ; Inner-loop byte counter
        LDX ZP_SPRITE_Y           ; Current screen row (0..191)
SMC_OPQ_ROW_HI_LO = *+1           ; Low of LDA abs,X operand --- patched
SMC_OPQ_ROW_HI_HI = *+2           ; High of LDA abs,X operand --- patched
        LDA SPRITE_SMC_INIT,X     ; runtime: LDA SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI,X or LDA SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2,X
        STA SMC_OPQ_STA_HI        ; Patch STA operand (high byte)
        LDA SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_LO,X  ; Row-low (fixed SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_LO table)
        STA SMC_OPQ_STA_LO        ; Patch STA operand (low byte)

; --- Inner loop: one iteration per sprite byte on this row ---
        LDX ZP_SPRITE_X           ; Destination column
.col_loop:
        CPX #$28                  ; Column >= 40 (off right edge)?
        BCS .col_skip             ;   yes --- transparent
SMC_TILE_SRC_LO = *+1             ; Low of LDA abs,Y operand --- caller sets
SMC_TILE_SRC_HI = *+2             ; High of LDA abs,Y operand --- caller sets
        LDA SPRITE_SMC_INIT,Y     ; Runtime: LDA (tile_src),Y
SMC_OPQ_STA_LO = *+1              ; Low of STA abs,X operand --- patched
SMC_OPQ_STA_HI = *+2              ; High of STA abs,X operand --- patched
        STA SPRITE_SMC_INIT,X     ; Store (opaque --- no OR, no zero skip)
.col_skip:
        INY                       ; Next sprite byte
        DEX                       ; Move left one column
        DEC ZP_SPRITE_ROW_REMAIN
        BPL .col_loop             ; More bytes on this row?

; --- Advance to next row ---
        INC ZP_SPRITE_Y           ; Next screen row
        DEC ZP_SPRITE_H           ; Rows remaining?
        BNE .next_row
        RTS
@ %def DRAW_SPRITE_OPAQUE SMC_TILE_SRC_LO SMC_TILE_SRC_HI

\section{Floor-enemy subsystem}

[[FLOOR_ENEMY_ADVANCE]] and [[FLOOR_ENEMY_DRAW]]
are the advance/draw pair for the \emph{floor-enemy} subsystem --- a
4-slot hostile-entity table (slots indexed [[X]]~=~$0\ldots 3$) driven by
the zero-page triple [[ZP_ENEMY_FLAG]]/[[ZP_ENEMY_COL]]/[[ZP_ENEMY_Y]] --- the same slots the player's laser beam
([[BEAM_UPDATE]]) targets and the same slots [[RESCUE_DRAW]] and
[[ENEMY_C_DRAW]] clear on a mutual-kill collision.

Each slot has three state bytes, one per slot:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[ZP_ENEMY_FLAG]]+X --- $[[$00]]$ = off, positive = moving
  rightward (advancing column by~$+5/+7/+9$), negative = moving leftward
  (advancing column by $-5/-7/-9$).  Bounds: a slot is despawned when
  its column leaves the $[[$8D]]\ldots [[$8F]]$ reachable window.
\item [[ZP_ENEMY_COL]]+X --- 8-bit column value.  Indexed into the
  [[PROJ_FRAME_IDX]] and [[PROJ_SCREEN_COL]] perspective tables (the
  same lookups used by the projectile hazard) to produce a
  sprite-frame index 0--6 and a screen column 0--39.
\item [[ZP_ENEMY_Y]]+X --- 8-bit screen row used directly as the sprite
  [[Y]] parameter for [[DRAW_SPRITE]].
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Advance handler.}  The MAIN\_LOOP JSR [[FLOOR_ENEMY_ADVANCE]]
walks slots $X=3 \ldots 0$.  A zero slot either stays idle or is
armed with a new spawn: the spawn fires only when the one-shot gate
at [[ZP_JUMP_FLAG]] is negative (the input handlers set this to
[[$FF]] on each jump-key press), and only when the level-data
spawn-schedule at [[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPAWN_SCHED]] indexed by
[[ZP_PLAYER_COL]] is non-negative.  The routine consumes the
jump-flag one-shot as soon as the first empty slot it encounters
takes it, and also clears it at the end of the loop if no slot
consumed it --- so at most one new floor-enemy spawns per
jump press.  The spawn plays a 10-click descending spawn click via
[[SND_DELAY_DOWN]] with [[A]]~=~[[$20]] and [[X]]~=~[[$0A]], then
inspects the main loop's [[SMC_MOVE_LEFT]] opcode byte: if that
byte is [[$20]] (the [[JSR]] opcode --- meaning left-movement is
currently active) the new slot becomes leftward-moving
([[ZP_ENEMY_FLAG]]~=~[[$FF]], [[ZP_ENEMY_COL]]~=~[[$3E]]); otherwise it
becomes rightward-moving ([[ZP_ENEMY_FLAG]]~=~[[$01]],
[[ZP_ENEMY_COL]]~=~[[$4A]]).  In either case [[ZP_ENEMY_Y]] is set to
the spawn-schedule-index~$+~9$.  Active slots advance column by
$\pm 5/\pm 7/\pm 9$ depending on [[ZP_MOVE_DIR]]: fastest when the
player is moving in the opposite horizontal direction (parallax),
slowest when moving with the slot.

\paragraph{Draw handler.}  The MAIN\_LOOP JSR [[FLOOR_ENEMY_DRAW]] also
walks slots $X=3 \ldots 0$.  Each active slot sets
[[ZP_SPRITE_Y]]~=~[[ZP_ENEMY_Y]], [[ZP_SPRITE_W]]~=~[[$01]],
[[ZP_SPRITE_H]]~=~[[$05]] (a 2-byte-wide $\times$ 6-row sprite per the
[[ZP_SPRITE_W]]~=~W--1 rule; see the [[DRAW_SPRITE]] W+1 bytes/row
memo), then looks up
[[PROJ_SCREEN_COL]]~$[$[[ZP_ENEMY_COL]]$]$ for the screen column and
[[PROJ_FRAME_IDX]]~$[$[[ZP_ENEMY_COL]]$]$ for a sprite-frame index
$Y=0\ldots 6$.  Finally a [[CPX]] cascade selects one of four 7-entry
sprite-pointer tables (one per slot), patches [[SMC_DS_SRC_LO]] /
[[SMC_DS_SRC_HI]], and calls [[DRAW_SPRITE]].

The four slot-specific sprite-pointer tables live in the swappable
level-1 region:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S3_LO]] / [[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S3_HI]]
  ([[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S3_LO]]/[[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S3_HI]], 7 entries) --- slot~3 sprite frames.
\item [[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S2_LO]] / [[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S2_HI]]
  ([[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S2_LO]]/[[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S2_HI]], 7 entries) --- slot~2 sprite frames.
\item [[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S1_LO]] / [[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S1_HI]]
  ([[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S1_LO]]/[[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S1_HI]], 7 entries) --- slot~1 sprite frames.
\item [[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S0_LO]] / [[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S0_HI]]
  ([[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S0_LO]]/[[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S0_HI]], 7 entries) --- slot~0 sprite frames.
\end{itemize}

The tables form a contiguous 28-entry block starting at
[[FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S3_LO]] (ending just before [[SPECIAL_BODY_POSE0_LO]]).

\paragraph{Historical naming.}  In earlier passes these routines were
misidentified as ``screen effects'' (advance) and ``score display''
(draw) based only on their position in the main loop between the
rendering and frame-end subsystems.  Tracing the actual code shows
both are dedicated to the 4-slot floor-enemy table; there is no
``score display'' JSR anywhere in [[MAIN_LOOP]].  Score digit drawing
is done inside [[POST_FRAME]] via [[DRAW_DIGIT]].

<<floor enemy sprite tables>>=

; --- Floor-enemy per-slot sprite-pointer tables (per-level data) ---
; Four 7-entry (LO, HI) table pairs in the swappable level-1 region
; $755C-$7577 / $765C-$7677.  Each table is indexed by a perspective
; frame index 0..6 (from PROJ_FRAME_IDX) to yield the sprite-data
; address for that slot at that perspective column.  The per-slot
; dispatch in FLOOR_ENEMY_DRAW picks one table by slot index X.


@

<<floor enemy advance defines>>=

; --- Floor-enemy spawn-schedule table (persistent, defined as a label
; in its ORG chunk inside the perspective-grid data region) ---
; 54-byte table (35 live + pad) indexed by ZP_PLAYER_COL.  A negative
; entry at the player's current column would suppress floor-enemy
; spawns; a non-negative entry allows spawning and also seeds the
; slot's row coordinate (spawn Y := schedule_index + 9).  Level-1
; data: indices 0..34 carry $25..$2E; later indices are 0 (spawn
; allowed with row $09, but gameplay keeps ZP_PLAYER_COL in the live
; range).

; --- Zero-page scratch used by FLOOR_ENEMY_ADVANCE ---
; ZP_ENEMY_SAVE_Y uses $1C as a one-byte save slot for Y across
; JSR SND_DELAY_DOWN so the spawn-index can be restored.  $1C is
; reused by many routines (see drol-scratch-slots notes); here it is
; local to the spawn path.
ZP_ENEMY_SAVE_Y = $1C           ; Y save across JSR SND_DELAY_DOWN

@ %def ZP_ENEMY_SAVE_Y

<<floor enemy advance>>=

        ORG $6683
FLOOR_ENEMY_ADVANCE:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; 4-slot floor-enemy AI tick and spawn handler.  Called from
        ; MAIN_LOOP.  Walks X=3..0 over ZP_ENEMY_FLAG[X]; $00 slots
        ; may spawn (gated on ZP_JUMP_FLAG one-shot and level-data
        ; schedule FLOOR_ENEMY_SPAWN_SCHED[ZP_PLAYER_COL]), positive
        ; slots advance rightward (+5/+7/+9), negative slots advance
        ; leftward (-5/-7/-9).  Advance step depends on ZP_MOVE_DIR:
        ; parallax gives fastest relative motion when the player
        ; moves opposite to the slot.  Spawn click is SND_DELAY_DOWN,
        ; spawn direction reads the main-loop SMC_MOVE_LEFT opcode
        ; byte at $67DD so new slots always approach from the
        ; player's current motion direction.  Slots despawn when the
        ; column leaves the reachable window (>= $8F right, >= $8D
        ; left after an extra -$02).
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_ENEMY_FLAG/COL/Y            --- 4-slot state arrays.
        ;   ZP_MOVE_DIR ($04)              --- player motion (parallax).
        ;   ZP_JUMP_FLAG ($05)             --- spawn one-shot ($FF=armed).
        ;   ZP_PLAYER_COL ($06)            --- schedule index.
        ;   FLOOR_ENEMY_SPAWN_SCHED+ZP_PLAYER_COL --- spawn schedule.
        ;   SMC_MOVE_LEFT byte ($67DD)     --- move-left active probe.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_ENEMY_FLAG/COL/Y, ZP_JUMP_FLAG (cleared),
        ;   ZP_DRAW_LOOP_IDX ($5C), ZP_ENEMY_SAVE_Y ($1C).
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

; --- Slot loop: X = 3 down to 0 ---
        LDX #$03
.slot_body:
        LDA ZP_ENEMY_FLAG,X             ; slot state byte
        BEQ .maybe_spawn                ; $00 -> inactive, try spawn
        BMI .advance_neg                ; negative -> advance leftward
        BPL .advance_pos                ; positive -> advance rightward

; --- Inactive slot: consume jump-flag one-shot to spawn one slot ---
.maybe_spawn:
        BIT ZP_JUMP_FLAG                ; one-shot gate
        BMI .spawn                      ; bit 7 set (= $FF) -> do spawn
.next_slot:
        DEX
        BPL .slot_body                  ; more slots
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_JUMP_FLAG                ; clear one-shot at loop end
        RTS

.spawn:
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_JUMP_FLAG                ; consume one-shot immediately
        LDY ZP_PLAYER_COL               ; schedule index
        LDA FLOOR_ENEMY_SPAWN_SCHED,Y
        BPL .spawn_do                   ; non-negative -> spawn allowed
        JMP .next_slot                  ; scheduled no-spawn for this col

.spawn_do:
        STX ZP_DRAW_LOOP_IDX            ; save slot index
        STY ZP_ENEMY_SAVE_Y             ; save schedule index
        LDX #$0A                        ; 10 clicks
        LDA #$20                        ; starting pitch
        JSR SND_DELAY_DOWN              ; descending spawn sound
        LDX ZP_DRAW_LOOP_IDX            ; restore slot index
        LDY ZP_ENEMY_SAVE_Y             ; restore schedule index
        LDA SMC_MOVE_LEFT               ; probe move-left opcode byte
        CMP #OPCODE_JSR                 ; $20 -> left-move is active
        BNE .spawn_right                ; not JSR -> spawn rightward
; --- Spawn leftward (entering from the right edge) ---
        LDA #$FF
        STA ZP_ENEMY_FLAG,X             ; state := leftward ($FF)
        LDA #$3E
        STA ZP_ENEMY_COL,X              ; start column := $3E
        TYA                             ; A := schedule index
        CLC
        ADC #$09
        STA ZP_ENEMY_Y,X                ; row := index + 9
        JMP .next_slot
; --- Spawn rightward (entering from the left edge) ---
.spawn_right:
        LDA #$01
        STA ZP_ENEMY_FLAG,X             ; state := rightward ($01)
        LDA #$4A
        STA ZP_ENEMY_COL,X              ; start column := $4A
        TYA
        CLC
        ADC #$09
        STA ZP_ENEMY_Y,X                ; row := index + 9
        JMP .next_slot

; --- Negative slot: delegate to advance_neg body below ---
.advance_neg:
        JMP .advance_neg_body

; --- Positive slot: advance column by +5/+7/+9, despawn past $8F ---
.advance_pos:
        BIT ZP_MOVE_DIR                 ; $04 player-move dir
        BEQ .pos_dir_zero               ; idle player -> slowest (+7)
        BMI .pos_dir_neg                ; player moving left -> fastest (+9)
; .pos_dir_pos: player moving right -> slowest (+5)
        LDA ZP_ENEMY_COL,X
        CLC
        ADC #$05
.pos_store:
        STA ZP_ENEMY_COL,X
        CMP #$8F
        BCS .despawn_pos                ; col >= $8F -> off the right
        JMP .next_slot
.pos_dir_zero:
        LDA ZP_ENEMY_COL,X
        CLC
        ADC #$07
        JMP .pos_store
.pos_dir_neg:
        LDA ZP_ENEMY_COL,X
        CLC
        ADC #$09
        JMP .pos_store
.despawn_pos:
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_ENEMY_FLAG,X
        JMP .next_slot

; --- Negative slot body: advance column by -5/-7/-9, despawn past $8D ---
.advance_neg_body:
        BIT ZP_MOVE_DIR
        BEQ .neg_dir_zero               ; idle player -> slowest (-7)
        BMI .neg_dir_neg                ; player moving left -> slowest (-5)
; .neg_dir_pos: player moving right -> fastest (-9)
        LDA ZP_ENEMY_COL,X
        SEC
        SBC #$09
.neg_store:
        STA ZP_ENEMY_COL,X
        SEC
        SBC #$02                        ; probe: col - 2
        CMP #$8D
        BCS .despawn_neg                ; col-2 >= $8D -> underflowed
        JMP .next_slot
.neg_dir_zero:
        LDA ZP_ENEMY_COL,X
        SEC
        SBC #$07
        JMP .neg_store
.neg_dir_neg:
        LDA ZP_ENEMY_COL,X
        SEC
        SBC #$05
        JMP .neg_store
.despawn_neg:
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_ENEMY_FLAG,X
        JMP .next_slot
@ %def FLOOR_ENEMY_ADVANCE

<<floor enemy draw>>=

        ORG $673B
FLOOR_ENEMY_DRAW:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; 4-slot floor-enemy perspective-grid draw.  Called from
        ; MAIN_LOOP.  For each active slot, projects ZP_ENEMY_COL
        ; through PROJ_SCREEN_COL / PROJ_FRAME_IDX, patches
        ; DRAW_SPRITE's source-pointer SMC from the slot-specific
        ; FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_Sn table, and calls DRAW_SPRITE.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_ENEMY_FLAG+X --- slot active flag (any non-zero = draw).
        ;   ZP_ENEMY_COL+X  --- slot column (index into projection).
        ;   ZP_ENEMY_Y+X    --- slot screen row.
        ;   PROJ_SCREEN_COL, PROJ_FRAME_IDX --- shared projection tables.
        ;   FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S0..S3_LO/HI --- per-slot sprite-pointer tables.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Outer loop: X=3..0.  Inactive (flag==0) -> next slot.
        ;   For active slots: load sprite geometry (W=1,H=5 =
        ;   2 bytes/row x 6 rows per DRAW_SPRITE's W+1 rule), compute
        ;   column index Y from PROJ_SCREEN_COL[$9F,X], frame index
        ;   Y' from PROJ_FRAME_IDX[$9F,X], patch DRAW_SPRITE source
        ;   from FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_Sn[Y'] per slot, save X into $5C
        ;   across the JSR, call DRAW_SPRITE.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_W/H/X/Y, $5C (X save),
        ;   SMC_DS_SRC_LO/HI inside DRAW_SPRITE.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

; --- Outer loop: scan slots X=3..0, drop inactive ---
        LDX #$03                        ; X = 3, 2, 1, 0
.find_active:
        LDA ZP_ENEMY_FLAG,X             ; $9B,X --- slot flag
        BNE .active                     ; non-zero: draw this slot
.next_slot:
        DEX
        BPL .find_active                ; more slots?
        RTS

; --- Active slot: set up DRAW_SPRITE parameters ---
.active:
        LDA ZP_ENEMY_Y,X                ; $A3,X --- screen row
        STA ZP_SPRITE_Y                 ; ZP_SPRITE_Y
        LDA #$01
        STA ZP_SPRITE_W                 ; ZP_SPRITE_W <- #$01 (2 bytes/row)
        LDA #$05
        STA ZP_SPRITE_H                 ; ZP_SPRITE_H <- #$05 (6 rows)
        LDA ZP_ENEMY_COL,X              ; $9F,X --- column value
        TAY
        LDA PROJ_SCREEN_COL,Y           ; projected column 0..39
        STA ZP_SPRITE_X                 ; ZP_SPRITE_X
        LDA PROJ_FRAME_IDX,Y            ; perspective frame index 0..6
        TAY                             ; Y' -> sprite-pointer table index

; --- Slot-specific sprite-pointer table dispatch ---
        CPX #$03
        BNE .not_s3
        LDA FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S3_LO,Y     ; Slot 3 frame source
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S3_HI,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        STX ZP_SAVE_X                   ; Save X across JSR
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        LDX ZP_SAVE_X                   ; Restore X
        JMP .next_slot
.not_s3:
        CPX #$02
        BNE .not_s2
        LDA FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S2_LO,Y     ; Slot 2 frame source
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S2_HI,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        STX ZP_SAVE_X
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        LDX ZP_SAVE_X
        JMP .next_slot
.not_s2:
        CPX #$01
        BNE .slot0
        LDA FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S1_LO,Y     ; Slot 1 frame source
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S1_HI,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        STX ZP_SAVE_X
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        LDX ZP_SAVE_X
        JMP .next_slot
.slot0:
        LDA FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S0_LO,Y     ; Slot 0 frame source
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA FLOOR_ENEMY_SPR_S0_HI,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        STX ZP_SAVE_X
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        LDX ZP_SAVE_X
        JMP .next_slot
@ %def FLOOR_ENEMY_DRAW

\section{Speaker click / delay loop}

[[SFX_TONE]] is the game's sole sound-effect generator.  It is
called from about eight sites --- the attract hazard animation, the
projectile hazard handler, the level-intro countdown tick, the
no-more-lives fanfare, and several level/game-event paths.

The routine is a classic Apple~II nested delay-loop speaker click:

\begin{itemize}
\item The accumulator on entry sets the pitch --- the number of
  inner-loop iterations (each about 7 cycles) before one speaker click.
\item The X register on entry sets the duration --- the number of
  clicks to emit.
\item The speaker access is done indirectly through zero-page pointer
  [[ZP_SFX_CLICK]] (2 bytes, at [[ZP_SFX_CLICK]] and
  [[ZP_SFX_CLICK]]+1).  The high byte is [[$C0]] (set at boot and
  never modified).  The low byte is either [[#<SW_SPEAKER]]
  ([[$30]], clicks the speaker) when sound is enabled, or
  [[#<SW_CASSOUT]] ([[$20]], points at the unused cassette-output
  soft-switch, silent) when sound is muted.
\end{itemize}

Making the speaker address data-driven this way lets the Ctrl-S mute
toggle (in [[INPUT_PROCESS]]) change sound state by flipping a single
bit in a ZP variable, with no branches on the hot path --- the
speaker-click instruction ([[CMP ($36),Y]]) still executes every
duration cycle but silently reads from an unused soft-switch when sound
is off.

The inner [[DEY/BNE]] loop also decrements Y back to zero before the
[[CMP ($36),Y]], so the indirect load always uses offset zero; the
wrap-around is harmless because every call enters with Y saved by the
[[TAY]] at the top of the outer loop.

<<sfx tone>>=

        ORG $67C1
SFX_TONE:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Speaker-click tone / delay generator.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A              --- pitch (inner-loop count, cycles per click).
        ;   X              --- duration (number of clicks to emit).
        ;   ZP_SFX_CLICK   --- low byte of speaker-click pointer
        ;                      (#<SW_SPEAKER = click, #<SW_CASSOUT = silent).
        ;   ZP_SFX_CLICK+1 --- high byte of speaker-click pointer (= $C0).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Outer loop (X iterations): TAY loads Y from pitch, the
        ;   DEY/BNE inner loop counts Y down to 0 (about 5*A + 5 cycles
        ;   of delay), then CMP,Y reads through the ZP pointer.  When
        ;   ZP_SFX_CLICK points at SW_SPEAKER this toggles the speaker;
        ;   when it points at SW_CASSOUT the read is silent.  X is then
        ;   decremented; when X reaches 0 the routine returns.
        ;
        ; Clobbers: A is preserved (CMP does not modify A), X=0 on exit, Y=0.

        TAY                     ; Y = pitch (reload every outer iteration)
.delay:
        DEY
        BNE .delay              ; Inner delay: Y counts down to 0
        CMP (ZP_SFX_CLICK),Y    ; Y=0; read SW_SPEAKER (click) or SW_CASSOUT (silent)
        DEX
        BNE SFX_TONE            ; Next click (reloads Y from A via TAY)
        RTS
@ %def SFX_TONE

\section{Entity draw dispatcher}

[[DRAW_ENTITIES]] is the last drawing call in [[MAIN_LOOP]]
(before [[POST_FRAME]] and the exit checks).  Despite the old
``page-flip'' nickname it does \emph{not} flip the hardware page --- that
is [[DISPLAY_PAGE_FLIP]].  Instead it is the frame-level
``restore-and-draw'' dispatcher for four independent sprite categories,
each with its own state table:

\begin{enumerate}
\item A small ``hit-entity'' restore pass (phase~1) that scans a 12-slot
  active table at [[ENTITY_HIT_STATE]] ([[$8D]],X bounded by [[ZP_HIT_MAX]]).  For the first active slot it restores two bytes of hi-res
  background at an address assembled from [[HIT_BG_HI]] ([[$0328]],X),
  [[HIT_BG_LO]] ([[$0334]],X) and the saved pixel pair [[HIT_BG_BYTE1]]
  ([[$0340]],X) / [[HIT_BG_BYTE0]] ([[$034C]],X).  The high byte is bumped by
  [[$20]] when [[ZP_PAGE_FLAG]] is negative so that the restore lands on the
  currently hidden hi-res page.  Control falls through into phase~2.
\item The \emph{player} sprite draw (phase~2), gated on
  [[$0E]] being non-negative.  The player column ([[ZP_PLAYER_Y]]+[[$10]])
  is looked up in parallel tables [[FLOOR_SPRITE_IDX]] and
  [[FLOOR_SCREEN_COL]] to produce a sprite-frame index and
  screen column.  Frame-counter bit~2 ([[$FD]]) selects between two
  sprite-data address tables (frame~A pair
  [[PLAYER_GRID_SPR_A_LO]]/[[PLAYER_GRID_SPR_A_HI]], frame~B pair
  [[PLAYER_GRID_SPR_B_LO]]/[[PLAYER_GRID_SPR_B_HI]]) whose entries
  are copied into the SMC operand slot inside the
  playfield sprite blitter at [[DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD]] ([[$65D5]],
  operand bytes at [[SMC_PFB_SRC_LO]] / [[SMC_PFB_SRC_HI]] = [[$6615]] /
  [[$6616]]).  The sprite row is [[FLOOR_TO_ROW]] indexed either
  by [[ZP_INTRO_Y]] during the intro/wait phase or by
  [[ZP_PLAYER_COL]] during gameplay --- selected by
  [[$1E]]~(zero means intro is still running).
\item A single ``special'' sprite (phase~3) --- most
  likely the moon-bouncing ball or an attract-mode actor --- gated on
  [[$AB]] being strictly positive.  Its floor-column index ([[$AC]]) is
  converted to an absolute screen position using [[FLOOR_BASE_ROW]] plus an offset [[$B9]],X (X from [[$AD]]), minus~[[$08]].  The
  result indexes [[FLOOR_SPRITE_IDX]]/[[FLOOR_SCREEN_COL]] the same way
  as phase~2; sprite-data table pair is
  [[SPECIAL_GRID_SPR_A_LO]]/[[SPECIAL_GRID_SPR_A_HI]] or
  [[SPECIAL_GRID_SPR_B_LO]]/[[SPECIAL_GRID_SPR_B_HI]]
  (bit~2 of frame counter), row comes from [[FLOOR_TO_ROW]] indexed by
  [[$AE]].
\item A two-slot ``companion'' draw (phase~4), gated on
  [[$33]] being non-negative.  Iterates X=1 down to 0 through three
  parallel per-slot tables in low ZP ([[$11,X]] = floor column,
  [[$13,X]] = X-offset, [[$15,X]] = floor row index).  Each slot uses
  the fixed sprite-data table at
  [[COMPANION_GRID_SPR_LO]]/[[COMPANION_GRID_SPR_HI]] (no animation toggle).
\item A 20-slot ``entity'' draw (phase~5).  Iterates
  Y=[[$13]] down to 0 through [[ENTITY_ACTIVE]] ([[$03A8]], activity), skipping
  slots that are zero or negative.  Parallel tables provide the
  floor-column ([[ENTITY_FLOOR_COL]] = [[$0358]]), X-offset index
  ([[ENTITY_XOFF_IDX]] = [[$036C]]), and floor row index
  ([[ENTITY_FLOOR_POS]] = [[$0380]]).  All twenty slots share the same
  sprite-data table at [[ENTITY_GRID_SPR_LO]]/[[ENTITY_GRID_SPR_HI]].
\end{enumerate}

Phases~2--5 each set up ZP sprite parameters ([[ZP_SPRITE_W]]/[[ZP_SPRITE_H]],
[[ZP_SPRITE_Y]], [[ZP_SPRITE_X]]) and
then [[JSR DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD]] --- the playfield variant of
[[DRAW_SPRITE]] whose inner loop rejects column~[[$0B]] (the
left playfield wall) and every column \$$\ge$~[[$1C]] (the right-side
HISCORE HUD panel), so gameplay sprites can't overwrite those fixed
screen regions.  They all patch the \emph{same} SMC operand bytes
([[$6615]]/[[$6616]] = [[SMC_PFB_SRC_LO]] / [[SMC_PFB_SRC_HI]]) inside that
blitter with sprite-specific source addresses before calling it.

The widths, heights and column indices per phase are:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|l|l|l|l}
Phase & [[$56]] (W) & [[$57]] (H) & Source base & State gate \\
\hline
Player      & 1 & 4 & [[PLAYER_GRID_SPR_A_LO]]/[[PLAYER_GRID_SPR_B_LO]] & [[$0E]] $\ge$ 0 \\
Special     & 1 & 3 & [[SPECIAL_GRID_SPR_A_LO]]/[[SPECIAL_GRID_SPR_B_LO]] & [[$AB]] $>$ 0 \\
Companion   & 1 & 2 & [[COMPANION_GRID_SPR_LO]] & [[$33]] $\ge$ 0 \\
Entities    & 1 & 5 & [[ENTITY_GRID_SPR_LO]]    & [[$03A8]],Y $>$ 0 \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\paragraph{Why this is the ``page-flip'' in MAIN\_LOOP.}  The routine
is called immediately after [[DISPLAY_UPDATE]] and before the frame
counter increment / [[POST_FRAME]] epilogue.  It is the final step
that commits all of the frame's sprite pixels to the hidden hi-res
page, which will become visible after [[DISPLAY_PAGE_FLIP]] runs on
the next frame.  The ``flip'' in the original label referred to the
[[ZP_PAGE_FLAG]]-driven [[$20]] page-offset applied in phase~1, not to
any toggle of the display soft-switch.

\paragraph{Cross-reference to [[LEVEL_INTRO_TICK]].}  Earlier prose
speculated that this chunk patches the same [[SMC_SR_HEIGHT]] /
[[SMC_SR_YSRC]] operands inside [[DRAW_PLAYER]]
that [[LEVEL_INTRO_TICK]] patches.  That was incorrect --- this
routine does \emph{not} touch those operands.  The two SMC slots
[[DRAW_ENTITIES]] patches are [[SMC_PFB_SRC_LO]] and
[[SMC_PFB_SRC_HI]], which are the source-address operand
bytes of the sprite-data fetch inside [[DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD]].

<<draw entities defines>>=

; --- Zero-page (entity draw dispatcher) ---
ZP_HIT_MAX      = $41           ; Max active hit-entity slot index (phase 1)
ZP_HIT_GATE     = $0E           ; $ff = suppress player draw (phase 2)
ZP_SPECIAL_A    = $AB           ; Special sprite state flag (phase 3)
ZP_SPECIAL_X    = $AC           ; Special sprite floor column (phase 3)
ZP_SPECIAL_Y    = $AD           ; Special sprite X-offset index (phase 3)
ZP_SPECIAL_ROW  = $AE           ; Special sprite floor row (phase 3)
ZP_COMPANION_GATE = $33         ; Companion-slot gate (phase 4)
ZP_COMPANION_COL  = $11         ; Companion floor-column pair (phase 4)
ZP_COMPANION_OFF  = $13         ; Companion X-offset pair (phase 4)
ZP_COMPANION_ROW  = $15         ; Companion floor-row pair (phase 4)
ZP_DRAW_DEST_LO = $FB           ; Phase-1 BG restore destination pointer (2 bytes)
ZP_DRAW_LOOP_IDX = $5C          ; Saved loop index for phases 4/5

; --- Hit-entity background-save tables (12 slots, parallel to ENTITY_HIT_STATE) ---
ENTITY_HIT_STATE = $8D          ; Hit-entity active flags ($8D,X, X<=ZP_HIT_MAX)
HIT_BG_HI       = $0328         ; High byte of BG-restore address (page 1 base)
HIT_BG_LO       = $0334         ; Low byte of BG-restore address
HIT_BG_BYTE1    = $0340         ; Saved BG byte at offset +1
HIT_BG_BYTE0    = $034C         ; Saved BG byte at offset +0

; --- 20-slot entity draw tables (phase 5) ---
; ENTITY_ACTIVE is defined as a label in the entity-tables chunk.
ENTITY_FLOOR_COL = $0358        ; Entity floor-column index table
ENTITY_XOFF_IDX = $036C          ; Entity X-offset index table
ENTITY_FLOOR_POS = $0380         ; Entity floor-row index table

; --- Floor-position lookup tables (player coord -> screen coords) ---
FLOOR_TO_ROW    = $1D40         ; Floor position -> sprite Y row
FLOOR_SPRITE_IDX = $1E00         ; Floor position -> sprite-frame index
FLOOR_SCREEN_COL = $1F00         ; Floor position -> sprite X column
; FLOOR_BASE_ROW at $188F is defined as a label in its own ORG chunk.

; --- DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD SMC aliases ---
; SMC_PFB_SRC_LO / SMC_PFB_SRC_HI are declared inline in the
; DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD chunk as "= *+1" / "= *+2" labels on the
; sprite-data LDA at $6614.  Each caller here patches them with the
; sprite-specific source address before JSR DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD.

; --- Perspective-grid sprite-pointer tables (per-level data) ---
; All six table pairs live inside the swappable level-1 region at
; $7500-$76FF loaded from track 5+ sector 1 (see the level1 pages
; 75-7A HEX chunk).  Each pair is indexed by a sprite-frame index
; fetched from FLOOR_SPRITE_IDX.  The entries point into the
; sprite-bitmap region at $8C00-$AFFF (per-level sprite sheet, also
; swappable).  Player and Special have two frames toggled by bit 2
; of $FD (frame counter); Companion and Entity use a single fixed frame.


@

<<draw entities>>=

        ORG $683C
DRAW_ENTITIES:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Per-frame entity draw dispatcher --- final drawing step of
        ; MAIN_LOOP.  Restores one hit-entity's hi-res background then
        ; draws player, one special, two companions and up to twenty
        ; entities onto the hidden hi-res page.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_HIT_MAX          --- max hit-entity slot to scan.
        ;   ENTITY_HIT_STATE,X  --- per-slot active flag.
        ;   HIT_BG_HI / HIT_BG_LO     --- BG-restore destination (page 1).
        ;   HIT_BG_BYTE0 / HIT_BG_BYTE1 --- saved BG byte pair.
        ;   ZP_PAGE_FLAG b7     --- negative: restore to page 2
        ;                                 (add $20 to HIT_BG_HI).
        ;   ZP_HIT_GATE         --- negative: skip player draw.
        ;   ZP_PLAYER_Y         --- player floor position (+$10).
        ;   ZP_HIT_FLAG         --- game-state word ($00 = intro).
        ;   ZP_INTRO_Y          --- intro sprite Y source.
        ;   ZP_PLAYER_COL       --- player sprite Y source.
        ;   $FD bit 2                 --- player/special animation phase.
        ;   ZP_SPECIAL_A..ROW ($AB-$AE) --- special-sprite slot state.
        ;   ZP_COMPANION_GATE   --- companion-slot gate.
        ;   ZP_COMPANION_COL/OFF/ROW  --- 2 companion slots ($11-$16).
        ;   ENTITY_ACTIVE ($03A8..$03BB) + parallel tables
        ;     ENTITY_FLOOR_COL, ENTITY_XOFF_IDX,
        ;     ENTITY_FLOOR_POS.
        ;   FLOOR_TO_ROW / FLOOR_SPRITE_IDX / FLOOR_SCREEN_COL /
        ;     FLOOR_BASE_ROW lookup tables.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Phase 1 scans ENTITY_HIT_STATE top-down for the first active
        ;   slot, then writes HIT_BG_BYTE0/BYTE1 back into,Y=0/1
        ;   where ($FC,$FB) is assembled from HIT_BG_HI (+$20 if the
        ;   page flag is negative) and HIT_BG_LO.  Falls through.
        ;   Phases 2--5 each set sprite dimensions / position, patch
        ;   SMC_PFB_SRC_LO/HI with a sprite-data source address, load
        ;   FLOOR_TO_ROW into ZP_SPRITE_Y and JSR DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   SMC_PFB_SRC_LO / SMC_PFB_SRC_HI,
        ;   ZP_DRAW_DEST_LO, ZP_DRAW_DEST_HI ($FC),
        ;   ZP_DRAW_LOOP_IDX, ZP_SPRITE_W/H,
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_Y/X, hi-res page framebuffers.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

; --- Phase 1: find topmost active hit-entity, restore its BG ---
.hit_scan:
        LDX ZP_HIT_MAX                  ; Start at highest slot
.hit_next:
        LDA ENTITY_HIT_STATE,X          ; Active flag
        BPL .hit_restore                ;   bit 7 clear = active
        DEX
        BPL .hit_next
        BMI .draw_player                ; X wrapped to $FF --- no hits
.hit_restore:
        LDA HIT_BG_HI,X                 ; High byte of saved BG address
        BIT ZP_PAGE_FLAG
        BPL .hit_bg_page1               ;   page flag positive: use as-is
        CLC
        ADC #$20                        ;   page flag negative: bump to page 2
.hit_bg_page1:
        STA ZP_DRAW_DEST_LO+1           ; ($FC) = high byte
        LDA HIT_BG_LO,X
        STA ZP_DRAW_DEST_LO             ; = low byte
        LDA HIT_BG_BYTE1,X              ; Saved pixel byte @ +1
        LDY #$01
        STA (ZP_DRAW_DEST_LO),Y         ; Restore to hi-res
        DEY
        LDA HIT_BG_BYTE0,X              ; Saved pixel byte @ +0
        STA (ZP_DRAW_DEST_LO),Y
;       fall through to phase 2

; --- Phase 2: player sprite ---
.draw_player:
        LDA ZP_HIT_GATE
        BMI .draw_special               ;   negative = suppress player
        LDA ZP_PLAYER_Y                 ; Player floor position
        CLC
        ADC #$10                        ;   + $10 (centre adjust)
        TAX
        TAY                             ; X = Y = player + $10
        LDA FLOOR_SPRITE_IDX,X          ; Sprite-frame index
        TAX
        LDA FLOOR_SCREEN_COL,Y          ; Screen column
        STA ZP_SPRITE_X
        LDA ZP_FRAME_COUNTER            ; Frame counter
        AND #$04                        ; Bit 2 = animation phase
        BEQ .player_frameA
        LDA PLAYER_GRID_SPR_B_LO,X
        STA SMC_PFB_SRC_LO
        LDA PLAYER_GRID_SPR_B_HI,X
        STA SMC_PFB_SRC_HI
        JMP .player_dims
.player_frameA:
        LDA PLAYER_GRID_SPR_A_LO,X
        STA SMC_PFB_SRC_LO
        LDA PLAYER_GRID_SPR_A_HI,X
        STA SMC_PFB_SRC_HI
.player_dims:
        LDA #$01
        STA ZP_SPRITE_W                 ; Width = 1 byte
        LDA #$04
        STA ZP_SPRITE_H                 ; Height = 4 rows
        LDX ZP_INTRO_Y                  ; Default: intro Y source
        LDA ZP_HIT_FLAG
        BEQ .player_row                 ;   $00 = intro running, keep $17
        LDX ZP_PLAYER_COL               ; Gameplay: use player column
.player_row:
        LDA FLOOR_TO_ROW,X
        STA ZP_SPRITE_Y
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD

; --- Phase 3: special sprite (moon-ball / attract actor) ---
.draw_special:
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_A
        BEQ .draw_companions            ;   $00 = inactive
        BPL .special_active             ;   positive = active
        BMI .draw_companions            ;   negative = inactive
.special_active:
        LDX ZP_SPECIAL_X                ; Floor column
        LDA FLOOR_BASE_ROW,X            ; Base floor row
        LDX ZP_SPECIAL_Y                ; X-offset index
        CLC
        ADC PERSPECTIVE_XOFF_BYTE,X     ; + per-entity vertical offset
        SEC
        SBC #$08                        ; - 8
        TAX
        LDA FLOOR_SCREEN_COL,X
        STA ZP_SPRITE_X
        LDA #$01
        STA ZP_SPRITE_W
        LDA #$03
        STA ZP_SPRITE_H
        LDA FLOOR_SPRITE_IDX,X
        TAX
        LDA ZP_FRAME_COUNTER
        AND #$04
        BEQ .special_frameA
        LDA SPECIAL_GRID_SPR_B_LO,X
        STA SMC_PFB_SRC_LO
        LDA SPECIAL_GRID_SPR_B_HI,X
        STA SMC_PFB_SRC_HI
        JMP .special_row
.special_frameA:
        LDA SPECIAL_GRID_SPR_A_LO,X
        STA SMC_PFB_SRC_LO
        LDA SPECIAL_GRID_SPR_A_HI,X
        STA SMC_PFB_SRC_HI
.special_row:
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        TAX
        LDA FLOOR_TO_ROW,X
        STA ZP_SPRITE_Y
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD

; --- Phase 4: two companion-slot sprites ---
.draw_companions:
        LDA ZP_COMPANION_GATE
        BMI .draw_entity_list
        LDX #$01                        ; Slots 1 then 0
.companion_loop:
        LDA ZP_COMPANION_COL,X          ; Floor column ($11,$12)
        TAY
        LDA FLOOR_BASE_ROW,Y            ; Base row
        STX ZP_DRAW_LOOP_IDX            ; Save X
        PHA                             ;   and accumulator
        LDA ZP_COMPANION_OFF,X          ; X-offset ($13,$14)
        TAX
        PLA
        CLC
        ADC PERSPECTIVE_XOFF_BYTE,X     ; + offset
        SEC
        SBC #$05                        ; - 5
        TAY
        LDA FLOOR_SCREEN_COL,Y
        STA ZP_SPRITE_X
        LDA #$01
        STA ZP_SPRITE_W
        LDA #$02
        STA ZP_SPRITE_H
        LDA FLOOR_SPRITE_IDX,Y
        TAY
        LDA COMPANION_GRID_SPR_LO,Y     ; Fixed source (no animation toggle)
        STA SMC_PFB_SRC_LO
        LDA COMPANION_GRID_SPR_HI,Y
        STA SMC_PFB_SRC_HI
        LDX ZP_DRAW_LOOP_IDX
        LDA ZP_COMPANION_ROW,X          ; Row index ($15,$16)
        TAX
        LDA FLOOR_TO_ROW,X
        STA ZP_SPRITE_Y
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD
        LDX ZP_DRAW_LOOP_IDX
        DEX
        BPL .companion_loop

; --- Phase 5: 20-slot entity list ---
.draw_entity_list:
        LDY #$13                        ; 20 slots
.entity_next:
        LDA ENTITY_ACTIVE,Y
        BEQ .entity_step                ;   $00 = inactive
        BMI .entity_step                ;   negative = inactive
        LDA ENTITY_FLOOR_COL,Y
        TAX
        LDA FLOOR_BASE_ROW,X
        PHA
        LDA ENTITY_XOFF_IDX,Y
        TAX
        PLA
        CLC
        ADC PERSPECTIVE_XOFF_BYTE,X
        SEC
        SBC #$05
        TAX
        LDA FLOOR_SCREEN_COL,X
        STA ZP_SPRITE_X
        LDA #$01
        STA ZP_SPRITE_W
        LDA #$05
        STA ZP_SPRITE_H
        LDA FLOOR_SPRITE_IDX,X
        TAX
        LDA ENTITY_GRID_SPR_LO,X
        STA SMC_PFB_SRC_LO
        LDA ENTITY_GRID_SPR_HI,X
        STA SMC_PFB_SRC_HI
        LDA ENTITY_FLOOR_POS,Y
        TAX
        LDA FLOOR_TO_ROW,X
        STA ZP_SPRITE_Y
        STY ZP_DRAW_LOOP_IDX
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD
        LDY ZP_DRAW_LOOP_IDX
.entity_step:
        DEY
        BPL .entity_next
        RTS
@ %def DRAW_ENTITIES

\subsection{Floor-position lookup tables}

Three parallel 256-entry tables at [[$1D40]]/[[$1E00]]/[[$1F00]] (total
697 live bytes spanning [[$1D47]]--[[$1FFF]]) convert a one-byte
``floor position'' index into the three sprite-draw parameters
consumed by [[DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD]] in every phase of
[[DRAW_ENTITIES]]:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[FLOOR_TO_ROW]] ([[FLOOR_TO_ROW_DATA]]) --- floor position to
  hi-res row.  Indices~0..25 all return row~0 (sky); from index~26
  the values ramp up to row~[[$21]] in 5-wide plateaus that widen
  toward the horizon, simulating vertical foreshortening.  The EQU
  base is [[$1D40]] but the first seven bytes are inter-chunk dasm
  gap fill (value [[$FF]]) that is never indexed at runtime; every
  real caller offsets by at least [[$07]].
\item [[FLOOR_SPRITE_IDX]] ([[FLOOR_SPRITE_IDX_DATA]]) --- floor
  position to 7-frame sprite-frame index ([[$00]]..[[$06]]).  The
  layout is a 28-byte cyclic ramp (four copies each of 0..6)
  repeated nine times, with four trailing zeros.  Every four steps
  of floor position advance one walk-cycle frame.  The resulting
  index then selects a sprite-data pointer from one of the six
  perspective-grid pointer pairs at [[PLAYER_GRID_SPR_A_LO]]
  through [[ENTITY_GRID_SPR_HI]].
\item [[FLOOR_SCREEN_COL]] ([[FLOOR_SCREEN_COL_DATA]]) --- floor
  position to hi-res byte-column ($X$, range [[$0C]]--[[$1E]]).
  Plateaus widen toward both edges in the same horizontal-
  foreshortening fashion: 16 entries at column [[$0C]] (distant
  left), 12-entry plateaus for the next few columns, widening to 16
  around the centre, then narrowing again on the right side.
  Mirrors [[FLOOR_TO_ROW]]'s vertical ramp.
\end{itemize}

All three tables are indexed together by the same derived index in
every phase of [[DRAW_ENTITIES]]: the caller computes the index
from slot state (player column, special X-offset, companion/entity
offsets) and the three tables return the sprite row, the sprite-
frame index (which selects the sprite-data pointer), and the screen
column for the blit.  Paired with the column-major
[[FLOOR_BASE_ROW]] (floor-column -> base row), this
four-table set fully describes the 3D-perspective projection of the
playfield grid into the 2D hi-res buffer.

\section{Level intro / countdown tick}

[[LEVEL_INTRO_TICK]] is the first subroutine called by
[[MAIN_LOOP]] each frame.  It implements the state machine that runs
between level transitions:

\begin{itemize}
\item When [[$1E]] is positive, the game is already running and this
  routine simply returns --- main-loop work proceeds normally.
\item When [[$1E]] is negative ([[$FF]] --- just after game start or a
  level transition), one-shot initialisation kicks in: the four
  movement slots, the input dispatcher slot and the sprite-render slot
  in the main loop are all patched to [[BIT]] ([[$2C]]) so that player
  control and sprite output are suspended during the intro.  Various
  state bytes are cleared; the countdown counter [[$18]] is set to
  [[$12]] (18 frames) and the auto-start timeout [[$19]] is set to [[$40]].
\item Once initialised ([[$1E == 0]]), the routine animates a
  countdown on every frame.  While [[$18 > 0]] it decrements $18 on
  odd frames and plays a tone/delay pulse through [[SFX_TONE]] with
  an amplitude fetched from the level-data byte [[$0200,$18]]; it also
  refreshes a sprite with a frame-dependent mask by patching the
  [[BIT]] slot at [[$65B7]] in [[DRAW_SPRITE]] into an [[AND #imm]] so
  the sprite flickers with the frame counter.
\item When the countdown reaches zero, the routine switches into a
  wait-for-start phase.  A software timer advances in [[$06]] and
  when it rolls over, the BCD lives counter [[ZP_LIVES_BCD]] is decremented.  If it goes negative the routine
  returns and the main-loop exit check at [[LIFE_LOST_HANDLER]] takes over
  (game-over path).
\item While waiting, the routine reads the keyboard, the two input
  handler slots ([[ZP_INPUT_1]] / [[ZP_INPUT_2]]) and the auto-start
  timeout counter [[$19]]; if any of those trip, the gameplay is
  activated: all entity-active slots in [[$8D]] are cleared, the
  main-loop input and sprite-render slots are restored to [[JSR]]
  opcodes, and [[$1E]] is set to [[$01]].  Otherwise a prompt sprite
  is drawn at a frame-dependent Y using sprite-table entry 1
  ([[SPRITE_TABLE_LO+1]] / [[SPRITE_TABLE_HI+1]]).
\end{itemize}

The routine also patches two ZP-aliased self-modifying operands in the
preceding game-engine chunks: the sprite-height immediate at
[[SMC_SR_HEIGHT]] ([[$64F6]], inside [[DRAW_PLAYER]]) and the Y-source
ZP operand at [[SMC_SR_YSRC]] ([[$64FA]], same routine).  On init it
re-points [[DRAW_PLAYER]] at the intro row in [[ZP_INTRO_Y]]; on
activation it restores the default $06 source and resets the
height immediate to [[$13]].

<<level intro defines>>=

; --- Zero-page (level-intro state) ---
ZP_INTRO_Y        = $17         ; Intro sprite Y row (also DRAW_PLAYER source during intro)
ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN = $18        ; Intro countdown frames remaining (starts at $12)
ZP_INTRO_TIMEOUT  = $19         ; Auto-start timeout counter (wraps through ZP_PAGE_FLAG to trigger)

; --- Level-data table consumed by the intro tick ---
LEVEL_DATA_BASE = $0200         ; Level data (ticks indexed 0..$12 via ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN)

; --- Main sprite pointer table (populated at runtime, indexed by sprite id) ---
SPRITE_TABLE_LO = $B000         ; Low bytes of sprite pointers ($B000-$B07F)
SPRITE_TABLE_HI = $B080         ; High bytes of sprite pointers ($B080-$B0FF)

; SMC_SR_HEIGHT / SMC_SR_YSRC are the self-modifying
; operand bytes inside DRAW_PLAYER; they are declared in the draw-player
; defines chunk.  LEVEL_INTRO_TICK patches them on init (to shrink the
; sprite and re-point it at ZP_INTRO_Y) and on activation (to restore
; the default $13 height and $06 Y source).

; --- Self-modifying operand slot inside DRAW_SPRITE ---
; SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP / SMC_SPRITE_MASK_ARG are declared
; inline in the DRAW_SPRITE chunk as "= *" / "= *+1" over a DC.B $24 $00
; pair (disk-image encoding of BIT ZP_PAGE_FLAG, a 2-byte NOP in the normal draw
; path).  LEVEL_INTRO_TICK patches them to AND #<flicker> during the
; countdown to flash the sprite, then restores the BIT opcode.

@

<<level intro tick>>=

        ORG $699C
LEVEL_INTRO_TICK:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Per-frame state machine for the level-start intro: countdown
        ; animation, tone pulses, wait-for-start, and activation.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_HIT_FLAG               --- state word
        ;                               $FF = needs init, $00 = intro running,
        ;                               $01 = gameplay active (fast RTS).
        ;   ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN  --- countdown frames remaining.
        ;   ZP_INTRO_TIMEOUT    --- auto-start timeout.
        ;   ZP_INTRO_Y          --- saved intro sprite Y row.
        ;   ZP_FRAME_COUNTER          --- flicker / parity source.
        ;   ZP_LIVES_BCD        --- BCD lives counter (goes negative = game over).
        ;   ZP_PLAYER_COL       --- saved on init; software timer
        ;                               during wait phase.
        ;   ZP_ACTION_DIR, ZP_JUMP_FLAG, ZP_FLOOR_MIRROR, ZP_ASC_FLOOR,
        ;   ZP_PLAYER_FLOOR_CUR, ZP_DSC_DIR, ZP_HIT_GATE, ZP_ENT_RESCUED,
        ;   ZP_EXTRA_LIVES        --- game-state scratch cleared
        ;                               or seeded on init/activation.
        ;   ZP_HIT_MAX                --- entity-slot count (cleared on wait).
        ;   FLOOR_THRESH[1]           --- per-level initial Y column.
        ;   ZP_INPUT_1 / ZP_INPUT_2 --- handler pointers
        ;                               whose MSB can trigger activation.
        ;   LEVEL_DATA_BASE,ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN
        ;                             --- tone amplitude for countdown step.
        ;   SPRITE_TABLE_LO+1 /
        ;   SPRITE_TABLE_HI+1         --- "ready" prompt sprite (id 1).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   ZP_HIT_FLAG > 0: RTS (fast path during gameplay).
        ;   ZP_HIT_FLAG < 0: one-shot init --- disable input / movement
        ;     / render SMC slots; clear state; save $06 into ZP_INTRO_Y;
        ;     point DRAW_PLAYER at ZP_INTRO_Y (SMC_SR_YSRC); set
        ;     ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN <- #$12, ZP_INTRO_TIMEOUT <- #$40;
        ;     ZP_HIT_FLAG <- #$00.  Falls through into the tick phase.
        ;   Tick phase (while ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN > 0): on odd frames
        ;     decrement the counter, decrement SMC_SR_HEIGHT and bump
        ;     ZP_INTRO_Y (unless ZP_ACTION_DIR suppresses).  Patch the
        ;     sprite mask SMC to AND #<ZP_FRAME_COUNTER|$80> for flicker,
        ;     draw the sprite via DRAW_PLAYER, restore BIT opcode, then
        ;     pulse SFX_TONE with the level-data byte at
        ;     LEVEL_DATA_BASE,ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN.
        ;   Wait phase (ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN == 0): software timer in
        ;     ZP_PLAYER_COL BCD-decrements ZP_LIVES_BCD when it wraps.
        ;     If ZP_LIVES_BCD goes negative, RTS (game-over path).
        ;     Otherwise clear entity-active table ENTITY_HIT_STATE[X]
        ;     for X in 0..ZP_HIT_MAX, poll keyboard / input-handler MSBs
        ;     / timeout; on trigger activate (ZP_HIT_FLAG <- #$01, restore
        ;     main-loop JSR slots, SMC_SR_YSRC <- #$06,
        ;     SMC_SR_HEIGHT <- #$13).  Otherwise draw the "ready" prompt
        ;     sprite (sprite-table id 1) at a row that dips by 2 on
        ;     every other frame once ZP_INTRO_TIMEOUT >= $F0.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_HIT_FLAG, ZP_INTRO_Y, ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN, ZP_INTRO_TIMEOUT,
        ;   ZP_ACTION_DIR, ZP_MOVE_DIR, ZP_JUMP_FLAG, ZP_PLAYER_COL,
        ;   ZP_FLOOR_MIRROR, ZP_ASC_FLOOR, ZP_PLAYER_FLOOR_CUR, ZP_DSC_DIR,
        ;   ZP_HIT_GATE, ZP_ENT_RESCUED, ZP_EXTRA_LIVES,
        ;   ENTITY_HIT_STATE[0..ZP_HIT_MAX] (entity-active table),
        ;   ZP_LIVES_BCD (BCD decrement),
        ;   SMC slots in MAIN_LOOP: SMC_INPUT, SMC_ASCEND,
        ;   SMC_DESCEND, SMC_MOVE_LEFT,
        ;   SMC_MOVE_RIGHT, SMC_RENDER,
        ;   SMC_SR_HEIGHT, SMC_SR_YSRC,
        ;   SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP, SMC_SPRITE_MASK_ARG,
        ;   SPRITE_PTR_LO, SPRITE_PTR_HI,
        ;   sprite-draw params ZP_SPRITE_W/H/Y/X.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

; --- Fast path: gameplay active ---
        LDA ZP_HIT_FLAG                 ; State word
        BMI .init                       ;   $FF = needs init
        BEQ .tick                       ;   $00 = intro running
        RTS                             ;   else (> 0) gameplay --- return

; --- One-shot initialisation ---
.init:
        LDA #$FF
        STA ZP_HIT_GATE                 ; Arm state byte
        LDA #$2C                        ; BIT opcode
        STA SMC_INPUT                   ; Disable input dispatch slot
        STA SMC_ASCEND                  ; Disable ascend slot
        STA SMC_DESCEND                 ; Disable descend slot
        STA SMC_MOVE_LEFT               ; Disable left slot
        STA SMC_MOVE_RIGHT              ; Disable right slot
        STA SMC_RENDER                  ; Disable sprite render slot
        LDA ZP_PLAYER_COL               ; Save current player column
        STA ZP_INTRO_Y                  ;   into intro Y
        LDA #$17
        STA SMC_SR_YSRC                 ; Re-point DRAW_PLAYER at ZP_INTRO_Y
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_JUMP_FLAG                ; Clear scratch
        STA ZP_HIT_FLAG                 ; State $00 = intro running
        STA ZP_MOVE_DIR                 ; Clear player horizontal move direction
        STA ZP_PLAYER_FLOOR_CUR         ; Clear scratch
        LDA #$D0
        STA ZP_PLAYER_COL               ; Seed player column
        STA ZP_EXTRA_LIVES              ; Seed paired state byte
        LDA #$40
        STA ZP_INTRO_TIMEOUT            ; $40 frames before auto-start
        LDA #$12
        STA ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN          ; 18 countdown frames
;       fall through into .tick

; --- Countdown / wait dispatch ---
.tick:
        LDX ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN
        BEQ .wait                       ; Countdown done --- wait-for-start
        LDA ZP_FRAME_COUNTER
        AND #$01
        BEQ .flicker_draw               ; Even frame: only draw
        DEX
        STX ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN          ; Odd frame: decrement counter
        LDA ZP_ACTION_DIR               ; Suppress row bump?
        BNE .flicker_draw
        DEC SMC_SR_HEIGHT               ; Shrink DRAW_PLAYER sprite height
        INC ZP_INTRO_Y                  ;   and nudge Y down one row
.flicker_draw:
; --- Draw flickering intro sprite via DRAW_PLAYER ---
        LDA #$29                        ; AND #imm opcode
        STA SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP          ;   patched into DRAW_SPRITE BIT slot
        LDA ZP_FRAME_COUNTER
        ORA #$80                        ; Force bit 7 of flicker mask
        STA SMC_SPRITE_MASK_ARG
        JSR DRAW_PLAYER                 ; Draw the intro sprite
        LDA #$24                        ; BIT zp opcode
        STA SMC_SPRITE_MASK_OP          ; Restore DRAW_SPRITE BIT slot
        LDY ZP_INTRO_COUNTDOWN
        LDA LEVEL_DATA_BASE,Y           ; Tone amplitude for this tick
        LDX #$0A
        JSR SFX_TONE                    ; Pulse the speaker / delay
        RTS

; --- Wait-for-start phase: BCD-decrement level timer ---
.wait:
        LDA ZP_PLAYER_COL
        BEQ .check_level                ; $06 == 0: skip timer roll
        INC ZP_PLAYER_COL
        BNE .done                       ; No rollover --- just return
        BIT KBDSTROBE                   ; Rollover: clear keystrobe
        SED
        SEC
        LDA ZP_LIVES_BCD
        SBC #$01
        STA ZP_LIVES_BCD                ; BCD decrement of on-screen lives
        CLD
.done:
        RTS

; --- Check lives counter, then wait for input or timeout ---
.check_level:
        LDA ZP_LIVES_BCD
        BPL .wait_input                 ; Positive: lives remaining --- keep waiting
        RTS                             ; Negative: game-over path

.wait_input:
        LDX #$01
        STX ZP_HIT_GATE
        STX ZP_FLOOR_MIRROR
        LDA FLOOR_THRESH,X              ; FLOOR_THRESH[1] = $84: per-level intro Y seed
        STA ZP_INTRO_Y
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_ACTION_DIR               ; Clear action flag
        LDA #$FF
        STA ZP_ENT_RESCUED
        LDX ZP_HIT_MAX                  ; Entity-slot count
.clear_entities:
        STA ENTITY_HIT_STATE,X          ; Mark slot inactive
        DEX
        BPL .clear_entities
        LDA #$06
        STA ZP_PLAYER_STANCE
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_LAST_DIR
        LDA KEYBOARD
        BMI .activate                   ; Key pressed --- start game
        LDY #$00
        LDA (ZP_INPUT_1),Y
        BMI .activate                   ; Input handler 1 asserts start
        LDA (ZP_INPUT_2),Y
        BMI .activate                   ; Input handler 2 asserts start
        INC ZP_INTRO_TIMEOUT
        BEQ .activate                   ; Timeout overflow --- auto-start

; --- Draw "ready" prompt sprite while waiting ---
        LDA ZP_INTRO_TIMEOUT
        CMP #$F0
        BCC .prompt_draw
        LDA ZP_FRAME_COUNTER
        AND #$01
        BEQ .prompt_draw
        LDA ZP_INTRO_Y
        SEC
        SBC #$02
        STA ZP_SPRITE_Y                 ; Dip two rows on alternating late frames
        JMP .prompt_params
.prompt_draw:
        LDA ZP_INTRO_Y
        STA ZP_SPRITE_Y
.prompt_params:
        LDA #$03
        STA ZP_SPRITE_W
        LDA #$0F
        STA ZP_SPRITE_H
        LDA #$14
        STA ZP_SPRITE_X                 ; X column 20
        LDA SPRITE_TABLE_LO+1           ; Sprite id 1 --- low
        STA SPRITE_PTR_LO
        LDA SPRITE_TABLE_HI+1           ; Sprite id 1 --- high
        STA SPRITE_PTR_HI
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        RTS

; --- Activation: restore main-loop slots and flip state to "running" ---
; The tail of this block (from RESUME_GAMEPLAY_SMC onward) is a second
; entry point jumped to by GAME_START_INIT --- the 13-byte SMC-patch
; that re-enables input and sprite rendering in MAIN_LOOP.  The prefix
; ($6A95..$6AA6) reseeds player column + gameplay-active flags and is
; only reached by falling through from the wait-for-start branch above.
.activate:
        LDA ZP_INTRO_Y
        STA ZP_PLAYER_COL               ; Restore player column
        LDA ZP_FLOOR_MIRROR
        STA ZP_BEAM_SEED_FLOOR
        STA ZP_DSC_FLOOR
        STA ZP_ASC_FLOOR                ; Seed floor-mirror, ascent, descent from ZP_FLOOR_MIRROR
        LDA #$01
        STA ZP_HIT_FLAG                 ; State = gameplay active
        STA ZP_DSC_DIR
RESUME_GAMEPLAY_SMC:
        ; Sub-entry: re-patch MAIN_LOOP's SMC slots to enable input
        ; dispatch and sprite rendering.  Called via [[JMP]] from
        ; GAME_START_INIT when starting (or restarting) a game.
        LDA #$06
        STA SMC_SR_YSRC                 ; DRAW_PLAYER reads ZP_PLAYER_COL again
        LDA #$20                        ; JSR opcode
        STA SMC_INPUT                   ; Re-enable input dispatch
        STA SMC_RENDER                  ; Re-enable sprite render
        LDA #$13
        STA SMC_SR_HEIGHT               ; Restore default sprite height
        RTS
@ %def LEVEL_INTRO_TICK RESUME_GAMEPLAY_SMC

\section{Special sprite: per-frame tick}

[[SPECIAL_TICK]] is the tick routine for the ``special''
sprite slot drawn by [[DRAW_ENTITIES]] phase~3 (see the
entity-draw-dispatcher section above).  It pairs with [[SPECIAL_DRAW]] the same way the three enemy slots pair their
[[advance]]/[[draw]] routines.  Both are called
unconditionally from [[MAIN_LOOP]], immediately after the HUD tile
update.

\paragraph{What the slot represents.}  The ``special'' sprite is a
bonus creature that walks horizontally across the playfield, colliding
with (and killing) floor-enemies in the four-slot [[$9B]] table that
[[ENEMY_C_DRAW]] and the beam subsystem target.  After four kills the
creature explodes into a fall/drift animation handled by the
[[SPECIAL_DRAW]] companion.  If the player's sprite overlaps the
drifting puff, the score is awarded [[$0500]] BCD via [[SCORE_ADD]] ---
five hundred points, the classic arcade ``catch a bonus'' payoff ---
and the slot returns to its inactive countdown.

\paragraph{Slot state machine.}  [[ZP_SPECIAL_STATE]] is the
one-byte state:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[$00]] --- inactive: an 8-bit timer in [[ZP_SPECIAL_POS]] is
  incremented each frame, and its wrap ($0\to1$ roll-over of the low
  byte) reseeds the slot by falling into the \emph{rearm} block at
  [[$6B14]].
\item [[$01]] (any positive value) --- active: advance the 16-bit
  position [[ZP_SPECIAL_POS]] by [[$0002]] per frame, and
  once it reaches [[$035A]] rearm the slot.  Set by the rearm block.
\item [[$FF]] (any negative value) --- drift: the sprite is
  falling/climbing after a 4-kill defeat; row [[$AE]] is moved down by 2
  per frame, but at the four ``ladder'' rows ([[$34]], [[$5C]], [[$84]], [[$AC]])
  \mbox{94\,\%} of frames return early with no motion and the
  remaining \mbox{$\sim$6\,\%} (gated on [[ZP_PRNG_A]] [[$5F]] $<$ [[$0F]])
  move the sprite \emph{up} by 2 rows before advancing~X.  Set by
  [[SPECIAL_DRAW]]'s collision handler after the fourth floor-enemy
  kill; cleared by the player-catch path inside [[SPECIAL_DRAW]] when
  the puff is collected.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Sound slot.}  [[ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR]] is a
twelve-step ascending-tone counter that plays one click per frame
through [[SND_DELAY_UP]] (duration~[[$0A]]) as it decrements
from~[[$0B]] down to~[[$00]], then idles at [[$FF]] (negative $\Rightarrow$
skip).  The pitch bytes live in the page-2 table
[[SND_PITCH_TBL_SPECIAL]] ([[$0218]], 12 entries).  The counter is armed
to~[[$06]] by [[SPECIAL_DRAW]] on the four-kill defeat edge --- a short
descending ``defeat jingle'' --- but is \emph{not} rearmed on the
normal per-cycle rearm at [[$6B14]], which is silent.  Cold start leaves
[[$B5]] at its zero-page residual; the BMI gate keeps the first
invocations silent until [[SPECIAL_DRAW]] arms it.

\paragraph{Rearm block ([[$6B14]]).}  Reached from the inactive-timer
wrap ([[INC $AC]]~$\Rightarrow$ 0) and from the end-of-transit
edge ([[$AC]] hits [[$5A]] with [[$AD]]=[[$03]]).  Resets [[ZP_SPECIAL_POS]] to
[[$003E]] (just past the rearm threshold so the next frame starts a fresh
traversal), picks a floor-row anchor from
[[ENEMY_C_ROW_TBL]]$[\hbox{PRNG}\bmod 4]$ (one of the three defined
entries at [[$85]]/[[$86]]/[[$87]]; index 0 reads the [[$84]] base byte which is
the same shared table as the enemy-C row reload), subtracts [[$0B]] to
place the sprite above the floor, arms [[ZP_SPECIAL_HP]] to~4
``hit points'' (the number of floor-enemies the sprite will kill
before exploding), and writes [[$01]] to [[ZP_SPECIAL_STATE]].

\paragraph{Why this was called ``SOUND\_UPDATE''.}  The previous EQU
stub name came from the prominent [[JSR SND_DELAY_UP]] at
the [[SND_DELAY_UP]] call in its sound path.  In fact every per-frame entity tick in Drol emits a
speaker-click via one of the three sound routines
([[SFX_TONE]]/[[SND_DELAY_DOWN]]/[[SND_DELAY_UP]]), and the tone here
is one of four simultaneous channels, not a dedicated sound
subsystem.  Renaming to [[SPECIAL_TICK]] aligns with the three other
``tick'' routines ([[ENEMY_A_ADVANCE]], [[ENEMY_B_ADVANCE]],
[[ENEMY_C_ADVANCE]]) and exposes the drift/rearm state machine that
was hidden by the old name.

<<special tick defines>>=

; --- Zero-page (special sprite slot) ---
; ZP_SPECIAL_STATE is the same byte aliased as ZP_SPECIAL_A in the
; draw-entities defines chunk.  Keep both names: the tick uses the
; state-machine reading, the draw uses the phase-3 activity gate.
ZP_SPECIAL_STATE = $AB          ; $00 inactive / positive active / negative drift
ZP_SPECIAL_POS   = $AC          ; 16-bit position; aliases ZP_SPECIAL_X/Y
; ZP_SPECIAL_ROW = $AE is declared in draw-entities defines (phase 3).
ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR = $B5        ; 12-step ascending-tone counter ($FF = idle)
ZP_SPECIAL_HP    = $08          ; Remaining floor-enemies to kill before defeat

; --- Page-2 sound pitch table ---
SND_PITCH_TBL_SPECIAL = $0218   ; 12 pitch bytes indexed by ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR
@

<<special tick>>=

        ORG $6ABA
SPECIAL_TICK:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Per-frame tick for the ``special'' bonus-creature slot drawn
        ; by DRAW_ENTITIES phase 3 (cf. SPECIAL_DRAW).  Emits
        ; one ascending-tone click, then dispatches on state:
        ; inactive, active (advance X), or drift (fall with ladder
        ; pauses).  On transit end, falls into the rearm sub-entry.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR  --- click-pitch index (BMI = idle).
        ;   ZP_SPECIAL_STATE    --- $00 inactive / +active / -drift.
        ;   ZP_SPECIAL_POS      --- 16-bit horizontal position.
        ;   ZP_SPECIAL_ROW      --- screen row (drift path only).
        ;   ZP_PRNG_A           --- 6%/94% split at drift-mode ladder
        ;                           rows; also reseed row anchor index
        ;                           on rearm.
        ;   ENEMY_C_ROW_TBL     --- 4-entry row table ENEMY_C_ROW_TBL..$87 (same
        ;                           shared table enemy-C reloads from).
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   1. Emit a click from SND_PITCH_TBL_SPECIAL[$B5] via
        ;      SND_DELAY_UP (duration $0A); skip when the counter is
        ;      negative.
        ;   2. State dispatch:
        ;      $00: jump to inactive-timer block at $6B32.
        ;      -  : drift path --- at ladder rows ZP_DIFF_THRESH_A/ZP_DIFF_TMP/$84/$AC the
        ;           PRNG gates a $-$2 row move (6%) vs. RTS (94%);
        ;           otherwise $+$2 row and fall into the X-advance.
        ;      +  : active path --- advance only (no row change).
        ;   3. X-advance: add $0002 to ZP_SPECIAL_POS/ZP_SPECIAL_Y.  If $AC $>=$ $5A and
        ;      $AD $=$ $03, fall into the rearm block; else RTS.
        ;   4. Rearm: reset $AC/$AD to $003E, pick a row
        ;      anchor from ENEMY_C_ROW_TBL,[PRNG&3] minus $0B, arm HP to 4, set
        ;      state to ZP_LAST_DIR, RTS.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR, ZP_SPECIAL_POS, ZP_SPECIAL_ROW,
        ;   ZP_SPECIAL_HP, ZP_SPECIAL_STATE, ZP_PRNG_A (via PRNG).
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

; --- Emit ascending-tone click ---
        LDX ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR
        BMI .after_click                ; Negative = idle
        LDA SND_PITCH_TBL_SPECIAL,X     ; Pitch byte
        LDX #$0A                        ; Duration = 10 clicks
        JSR SND_DELAY_UP                ; Ascending tone
        DEC ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR
.after_click:

; --- State dispatch ---
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_STATE
        BEQ .inactive_hop               ; $00 = inactive -> timer jump
        BMI .drift                      ; $80+ = drift/dying
        BPL .advance                    ; $01..$7F = active
.inactive_hop:
        JMP .inactive_timer             ; (out-of-reach relative branch)

; --- Drift: fall with ladder-row pauses ---
.drift:
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        CMP #$34
        BEQ .at_ladder
        CMP #$5C
        BEQ .at_ladder
        CMP #$84
        BEQ .at_ladder
        CMP #$AC
        BEQ .at_ladder
        CLC
        ADC #$02                        ; Not at ladder: row += 2 (fall)
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        JMP .advance
.at_ladder:
        LDA ZP_PRNG_A
        CMP #$0F
        BCS .exit                       ; ~94%: stay put at ladder
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        SEC
        SBC #$02                        ; ~6%: climb up one rung
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_ROW

; --- Advance 16-bit X position by ZP_ACTION_DIR ---
.advance:
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_POS
        CLC
        ADC #$02
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_POS
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_POS+1
        ADC #$00
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_POS+1
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_POS
        CMP #$5A
        BCS .check_end                  ; Low >= $5A: maybe end of transit
.exit:
        RTS
.check_end:
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_POS+1
        CMP #$03
        BNE .exit                       ; High != 3: keep going

; --- Rearm slot (entered via fall-through or JMP from timer wrap) ---
SPECIAL_REARM:
        LDA #$3E
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_POS              ; Reset position to $003E
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_POS+1
        JSR PRNG                        ; Random row-anchor index
        AND #$03
        TAX
        LDA ENEMY_C_ROW_TBL,X           ; $84/$85/$86/$87
        SEC
        SBC #$0B                        ; Rise above floor
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        LDA #$04
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_HP               ; 4 HP (kills before defeat)
        LDA #$01
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_STATE            ; Activate
.rearm_rts:
        RTS

; --- Inactive timer: increment $AC; wrap triggers rearm ---
; Reuses .rearm_rts above as its not-yet-wrapped return.
.inactive_timer:
        INC ZP_SPECIAL_POS
        BNE .rearm_rts                  ; Not yet wrapped: return
        JMP SPECIAL_REARM               ; Wrap: rearm slot
@ %def SPECIAL_TICK SPECIAL_REARM ZP_SPECIAL_STATE ZP_SPECIAL_POS ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR ZP_SPECIAL_HP SND_PITCH_TBL_SPECIAL

\section{Special sprite: per-frame draw}

[[SPECIAL_DRAW]] is the direct draw partner of
[[SPECIAL_TICK]].  Both are invoked unconditionally from [[MAIN_LOOP]]
each frame; [[SPECIAL_TICK]] updates the slot's timer/state and
[[SPECIAL_DRAW]] renders the sprite and handles both of its collision
tests (four-kill body-collision with the floor-enemy table, and the
drift-puff player-catch).

\paragraph{Three visual phases.}  The routine gates on
[[ZP_SPECIAL_STATE]] just like the tick:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[$00]] (\textbf{inactive}) --- fall through to [[SPECIAL_INACTIVE_DRAW]], a 29-byte helper that draws a small [[$02]]$\times$[[$06]] marker
  sprite from the level-data pointer pair at [[SPECIAL_PEEK_LO]]/[[SPECIAL_PEEK_HI]] at a
  fixed screen position derived from the slot's row anchor ([[$AE]]).
  Conceptually the ``peek'' of the creature waiting off-screen.
\item positive (\textbf{active}) --- perspective-transform the 16-bit
  position [[ZP_SPECIAL_POS]] against the player's world-X, draw a
  [[$06]]$\times$[[$14]] body sprite, and run a hit test against the
  four-slot floor-enemy table at [[$9B]]/[[$9F]]/[[$A3]] (the same slots
  targeted by [[ENEMY_C_DRAW]] and the beam subsystem).  On a floor-enemy
  overlap: clear that slot ($[[$00]] \to [[$9B]][X]$), decrement
  [[ZP_SPECIAL_HP]], and on the fourth kill (HP $=0$) set
  drift mode and arm the defeat-jingle sound counter.
\item negative (\textbf{drift}) --- draw a [[$04]]$\times$[[$0F]] puff
  sprite from the per-perspective-frame pointer table
  [[SPECIAL_PUFF_LO]]/[[SPECIAL_PUFF_HI]] ([[$AFDA]]/[[$B05A]], indexed by
  the same perspective-frame-index Y the body path uses), then test
  whether the player's sprite overlaps the puff.  On a catch: award
  [[$0500]] BCD via [[SCORE_ADD]], clear [[ZP_SPECIAL_STATE]], arm
  [[ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR_B]] to~4 for a short catch tone, and
  bump the position so the slot immediately falls into its inactive
  countdown.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{SMC-chained walk-cycle body draw.}  Unlike the three enemy
slots --- which index a per-frame sprite table directly from
[[ZP_FRAME_COUNTER]] bits --- [[SPECIAL_DRAW]]'s body path uses a
\emph{self-modifying dispatch}: a [[JMP]] inside [[SPECIAL_DRAW]]'s body path whose operand bytes
[[SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_LO]]/[[SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_HI]] point
to one of six small handlers in the [[<<special body draw steps>>]] chunk.  Each handler rewrites
the operand bytes to the \emph{next} handler in a ring, then patches
[[SMC_DS_SRC_LO]]/[[SMC_DS_SRC_HI]] with its own sprite source pointer
and calls [[DRAW_SPRITE]].  The six handlers select from a four-entry
per-level sprite-pointer table at [[SPECIAL_BODY_POSE0_LO]]/[[HI]]..[[SPECIAL_BODY_POSE3_LO]]/[[HI]] using
offsets $\{0, 7, 14, 21, 14, 7\}$ --- a \emph{palindromic} walk cycle
(poses 0, 1, 2, 3, 2, 1) that gives the creature a bidirectional
walk-in-place look without storing a frame index in RAM.  The initial
operand [[$6C3F]] on disk starts the cycle at handler~1.

\paragraph{Which [[DRAW_SPRITE]] variant.}  All four sub-draws
([[SPECIAL_INACTIVE_DRAW]], the six body steps, the drift-puff, and
the defeat transition) call [[DRAW_SPRITE]] --- not
[[DRAW_SPRITE_PLAYFIELD]].  This is the same transparent-OR
blit used by the three enemy slots (and distinct from the playfield
blit used by [[DRAW_ENTITIES]]).  SMC source pointers go to
[[SMC_DS_SRC_LO]]/[[SMC_DS_SRC_HI]], the
[[DRAW_SPRITE]] operand bytes, not the playfield variant.

\paragraph{Sound slot.}  [[SPECIAL_DRAW]] drives a \emph{second} sound
counter [[ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR_B]] with a companion pitch table
[[SND_PITCH_TBL_SPECIAL_B]].  Unlike the ascending-tone
counter the tick uses, this one clicks through [[SFX_TONE]] at
duration [[$08]] --- a shorter, higher click.  It is armed to~[[$04]] on
the player-catches-puff edge, producing a four-click ``pickup'' tone.
[[$B6]] also idles at negative (BMI skips the click).

\paragraph{Player-overlap boxes.}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Body-phase catch} (fires on the same frame as
  the fourth-kill defeat, i.e.\ when the creature explodes under the
  player): X-box [[[$40]], [[$56]]) on the transformed screen-X
  [[$AF]]; Y-box [[$06-$13, $06+$12]] on [[$AE]].  Wins set the
  hit-flag [[ZP_HIT_FLAG]] = [[$FF]].
\item \textbf{Drift-phase catch}: X-box [[[$40]], [[$53]]), Y-box
  [[$06-$0E, $06+$12]] on [[$AE]].  Wins award +[[$0500]] BCD and reset
  the slot.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Perspective transform} (same shape as the enemy draws).
[[ZP_PLAYER_Y]] indexes
[[PERSPECTIVE_XOFF_LO]]/[[PERSPECTIVE_XOFF_HI]] minus
[[ZP_SPRITE_XREF]] to produce the player's world-X; subtracting
that from the creature's 16-bit [[ZP_SPECIAL_POS]] yields the
transformed screen-X in [[$AF]].  An off-screen test (high byte $\ne 0$
or low byte $\ge [[$A0]]$) short-circuits the draw with an RTS.  [[$AF]]
is then used as the index into [[PROJ_SCREEN_COL]] (the
horizontal-to-screen-column table) and [[PROJ_FRAME_IDX]]
(horizontal-to-sprite-frame-index).

\paragraph{Why the previous ``ANIM\_UPDATE'' stub was wrong.}  The old
name described a superficial reading: the SMC-chained dispatch writes
bytes during execution, which resembles an animation update.  In fact
the SMC is an optimisation for a single sprite-slot \emph{draw} ---
the routine is the draw partner of [[SPECIAL_TICK]], emitting the
sprite, running two collision tests, awarding score, and managing the
defeat/catch state transitions.

\paragraph{Body-sprite art.}  Figure~\ref{fig:special_body_sprites}
shows all 28 body frames: four poses (the palindromic ring visits
them in order \{0,\,1,\,2,\,3,\,2,\,1\}) across seven perspective
depths.  Each body sprite is $[[$07]]\times[[$14]]$ in bytes
([[ZP_SPRITE_W]]~=~[[$06]], [[ZP_SPRITE_H]]~=~[[$14]]).  The drift-mode
puff set is shown in Figure~\ref{fig:special_puff_sprites}, and the
single $[[$03]]\times[[$06]]$ ``peek'' marker drawn during the inactive
countdown is included in Figure~\ref{fig:enemy_c_auxiliary} above.
All special-slot sprites live in the swappable level-data region
([[SPECIAL_PEEK_DATA]] for the peek through [[$9D00]]+ for the body
poses) and were extracted from [[drol.dsk]] phase~0.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{images/special_body_sprites.png}
\caption{[[SPECIAL_DRAW]] body sprites, four poses $\times$ seven
perspective frames.  The SMC ring visits poses 0, 1, 2, 3, 2, 1,
producing a six-frame palindromic walk cycle.}
\label{fig:special_body_sprites}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{images/special_puff_sprites.png}
\caption{[[SPECIAL_PUFF]] drift-mode puff sprites at
$[[$05]]\times[[$0F]]$ (W=[[$04]], H=[[$0F]]), seven perspective frames indexed
by Y~=~perspective-frame-index from [[PROJ_FRAME_IDX]].  Drawn by
the [[.drift_puff]] branch of [[SPECIAL_DRAW]].}
\label{fig:special_puff_sprites}
\end{figure}

<<special draw defines>>=

; --- Zero-page (special slot, draw side) ---
; (ZP_SPECIAL_STATE, ZP_SPECIAL_POS, ZP_SPECIAL_ROW, ZP_SPECIAL_HP,
;  ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR are declared in special-tick-defines and
;  draw-entities-defines.)
ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR_B = $B6      ; Defeat/catch jingle counter (BMI = idle)
ZP_SCREEN_X     = $AF           ; Transformed screen X scratch (body/puff)
ZP_SCREEN_X_HI  = $B0           ; High byte of transformed screen X

; --- Page-2 sound pitch table for ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR_B ---
SND_PITCH_TBL_SPECIAL_B = $021F ; 4+ pitch bytes indexed by ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR_B

; --- Sprite-pointer tables ---
; SPRITE_TABLE_LO/HI is the main sprite-pointer table;
; the special slot uses a family at offset KEY_DESCEND / $5A (i.e.\
; $AFDA/$B05A) indexed by the perspective-frame index. This
; family covers the drift-phase ``puff'' pointers, one pair per
; scale-factor, so the puff shrinks with distance.
SPECIAL_PUFF_LO = $AFDA         ; Drift-puff pointer table, low bytes
SPECIAL_PUFF_HI = $B05A         ; Drift-puff pointer table, high bytes

; --- Walk-cycle body sprite base pointers ---
; Four poses in the per-level sprite tables SPECIAL_BODY_POSE0..3 (LO/HI),
; indexed by Y (perspective-frame index from PROJ_FRAME_IDX).  The six
; SMC handlers visit them in order {0, 1, 2, 3, 2, 1} then cycle.

; --- Inactive-phase marker sprite (single pointer) ---
; One byte after ENEMY_C_PUFF and one before ENEMY_B_PUFF
;; a per-level pointer to the small ZP_ACTION_DIRx$06 ``peek''
; sprite drawn while the slot is counting down to spawn.
@

<<special draw>>=

        ORG $6B39
SPECIAL_DRAW:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Per-frame draw + collision handler for the ``special''
        ; bonus-creature slot; direct draw partner of SPECIAL_TICK.
        ; Three-way dispatch on ZP_SPECIAL_STATE:
        ;   $00  inactive --> tail JMP to SPECIAL_INACTIVE_DRAW
        ;   $01+ active   --> perspective transform, 4-slot
        ;                     floor-enemy kill-box, JMP through
        ;                     SMC ring to one of six body-walk handlers.
        ;   $80+ drift    --> perspective transform, draw puff from
        ;                     SPECIAL_PUFF table, test player catch,
        ;                     award +$0500 BCD on catch and reset slot.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_SPECIAL_STATE, ZP_SPECIAL_POS (16-bit), ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        ;   ZP_SPECIAL_HP, ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR_B
        ;   ZP_PLAYER_Y, ZP_PLAYER_COL, ZP_SPRITE_XREF
        ;   Floor-enemy slots KEY_ESC / $9F / $A3 (4 slots each)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   1. Emit a SFX_TONE click (duration $08) indexed by
        ;      SND_PITCH_TBL_SPECIAL_B[$B6] if $B6 >= 0; dec $B6.
        ;   2. $AB == 0 --> JMP SPECIAL_INACTIVE_DRAW.
        ;   3. Perspective-transform $AC/$AD against player world-X into
        ;      $AF (lo) / $B0 (hi).  RTS if off-screen (hi != 0 or
        ;      lo >= $A0).
        ;   4. Prepare sprite column from PROJ_SCREEN_COL[X], sprite
        ;      frame Y from PROJ_FRAME_IDX[X] (for sprite-table indexing).
        ;   5. If $AB < 0 (drift): JMP .drift_puff at $6BEB.
        ;   6. Else (active): draw 6x20 body, kill-box test against
        ;      floor-enemies, maybe trigger defeat, JMP .dispatch_body.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_SCREEN_X, ZP_SCREEN_X_HI, ZP_SPRITE_W/H/X/Y, $9B[X], $08,
        ;   ZP_SPECIAL_STATE, ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR, ZP_SPECIAL_ROW,
        ;   SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_LO/HI, SMC_DS_SRC_LO/HI, $1E (hit flag).
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

; --- Emit catch/defeat-jingle click ---
        LDX ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR_B
        BMI .after_click                ; Negative = idle
        LDA SND_PITCH_TBL_SPECIAL_B,X   ; Pitch byte
        LDX #$08                        ; Duration = 8 clicks
        JSR SFX_TONE
        DEC ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR_B
.after_click:

; --- State dispatch on $AB ---
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_STATE
        BNE .active_or_drift            ; Non-zero = draw somehow
        JMP SPECIAL_INACTIVE_DRAW       ; $00 = inactive marker draw
.active_or_drift:

; --- Perspective transform: screen_X = creature_pos - player_world_x ---
        LDX ZP_PLAYER_Y                 ; $4A -> perspective-table index
        LDA PERSPECTIVE_XOFF_LO,X       ; Y -> world-X offset (lo)
        SEC
        SBC ZP_SPRITE_XREF              ; - level's X reference
        STA ZP_SCREEN_X                 ; ZP_SCREEN_X = player world-X (lo)
        LDA PERSPECTIVE_XOFF_HI,X       ; Y -> world-X offset (hi)
        SBC #$00                        ; (borrow from lo)
        STA ZP_SCREEN_X_HI              ; ZP_SCREEN_X_HI = player world-X (hi)
        SEC
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_POS
        SBC ZP_SCREEN_X                 ; - player world-X (lo)
        STA ZP_SCREEN_X
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_POS+1
        SBC ZP_SCREEN_X_HI              ; - player world-X (hi)
        BEQ .on_screen                  ; hi == 0 = on screen
.off_screen:
        RTS                             ; off-screen: early RTS (shared)
.on_screen:
        LDA ZP_SCREEN_X
        CMP #$A0                        ; >= $A0 = too far right
        BCS .off_screen                 ; take the early RTS
        TAX                             ; X = screen X for PROJ tables

; --- Common sprite-parameter setup ---
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        STA ZP_SPRITE_Y                 ; Sprite row
        LDA PROJ_SCREEN_COL,X
        STA ZP_SPRITE_X                 ; Sprite column
        LDA PROJ_FRAME_IDX,X
        TAY                             ; Y = sprite-frame index

; --- Branch to drift if ZP_SPECIAL_A < 0 ---
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_STATE
        BMI .drift_puff                 ; Drift -> puff branch

; --- Active body path: prepare body-sprite size, run kill-box test ---
        LDA #$06                        ; Body: W = 6
        STA ZP_SPRITE_W
        LDA #$14                        ; Body: H = 20
        STA ZP_SPRITE_H
        LDX #$03                        ; Walk 4-slot enemy table X = 3..0
.find_enemy:
        LDA ZP_ENEMY_FLAG,X             ; ZP_ENEMY_FLAG[X] --- active?
        BNE .check_box                  ;   non-zero = try kill-box
.try_next_enemy:
        DEX
        BPL .find_enemy                 ;   continue X = 3..0
        JMP .no_kill                    ; no active enemy: skip kill-box
.check_box:
; Kill-box: X-range [pos-$0F, pos) AND Y-range [row-$0F, row) on enemy slot
        LDA ZP_SCREEN_X
        CMP ZP_ENEMY_COL,X
        BCC .try_next_enemy             ;   X < enemy_x
        SEC
        SBC #$0F                        ;   pos - $0F
        CMP ZP_ENEMY_COL,X
        BCS .try_next_enemy             ;   X - $0F >= enemy_x (too far)
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        CMP ZP_ENEMY_Y,X
        BCS .try_next_enemy             ;   Y >= enemy_y (below)
        CLC
        ADC #$0F
        CMP ZP_ENEMY_Y,X
        BCC .try_next_enemy             ;   Y + $0F < enemy_y (above)
; Kill: clear enemy slot, dec HP, maybe trigger defeat
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_ENEMY_FLAG,X             ; ZP_ENEMY_FLAG[X] = 0 (kill floor enemy)
        DEC ZP_SPECIAL_HP
        BNE .dispatch_body              ; HP != 0: skip defeat + catch
; Defeat edge: enter drift, arm defeat jingle, bump row
        LDA #$FF
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_STATE            ; ZP_SPECIAL_A <- #$FF -> drift mode
        LDA #$06
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR          ; Arm ascending-tone jingle
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        CLC
        ADC #$03
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_ROW              ; Row += 3 (fall start)
        ; Fall through into the catch box below (defeat edge only).
.no_kill:

; --- Body-phase player-catch box (triggers hit-flag only) ---
; Note: only reached on .no_kill fall-through (no-active-enemy case)
; or after defeat-edge fall-through (HP reached 0 this frame).  HP>0
; kills skip straight to .dispatch_body to bypass this test.
        LDA ZP_SCREEN_X
        CMP #$40
        BCC .dispatch_body              ; X < $40
        CMP #$56
        BCS .dispatch_body              ; X >= $56
        LDA ZP_PLAYER_COL
        SEC
        SBC #$13                        ; player_col - $13
        CMP ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        BCS .dispatch_body              ; row <= player_col-$13
        CLC
        ADC #$25                        ; -> player_col + $12
        CMP ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        BCC .dispatch_body              ; row > player_col+$12
        LDA #$FF
        STA ZP_HIT_FLAG                 ; Hit flag = $FF
.dispatch_body:
        JMP SPECIAL_BODY_STEP1          ; SMC: operand bytes rewritten
SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_LO = *-2               ;   by handlers+ to walk
SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_HI = *-1               ;   the 6-step palindromic cycle.

; --- Drift-phase puff draw + player-catch (award +$0500 BCD) ---
.drift_puff:
        LDA #$04
        STA ZP_SPRITE_W                 ; Puff: W = 4
        LDA #$0F
        STA ZP_SPRITE_H                 ; Puff: H = 15
        LDA SPECIAL_PUFF_LO,Y           ; Y-indexed per-scale puff pointer
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA SPECIAL_PUFF_HI,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE                 ; Transparent OR blit
; Drift-phase catch box: X in [$40, $53), Y in [player_col-$0E, +$12]
        LDA ZP_SCREEN_X
        CMP #$40
        BCC .drift_done                  ; X < $40
        CMP #$53
        BCS .drift_done                  ; X >= $53
        LDA ZP_PLAYER_COL
        SEC
        SBC #$0E                        ; player_col - $0E
        CMP ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        BCS .drift_done
        CLC
        ADC #$20                        ; -> player_col + $12
        CMP ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        BCC .drift_done
; Catch: clear slot, arm catch-jingle, award +$0500 BCD
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_STATE            ; Back to inactive
        LDA #$04
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR_B        ; Arm catch tone (4 clicks)
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_SCORE_ADD_LO             ; +$0500 BCD
        LDA #$05
        STA ZP_SCORE_ADD_HI
        JSR SCORE_ADD
        LDA #$D0
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_POS              ; Reseed 8-bit inactive timer
        LDA ZP_SCREEN_X
        SEC
        SBC #$02
        STA ZP_SPECIAL_POS+1            ; Seed $AD (carried through)
        INC ZP_SPECIAL_ROW              ; Bump row by 2 (fall-through look)
        INC ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
.drift_done:
        RTS
@ %def SPECIAL_DRAW SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_LO SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_HI ZP_SPECIAL_SND_CTR_B SND_PITCH_TBL_SPECIAL_B SPECIAL_PUFF_LO SPECIAL_PUFF_HI ZP_SCREEN_X ZP_SCREEN_X_HI

<<special body draw steps>>=

        ORG $6C3F
; ---------------------------------------------------------------------
; Six SMC-chained body-walk handlers for SPECIAL_DRAW.
;
; The active-path JMP at $6BE8 has operand bytes $6BE9/$6BEA
; (SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_LO/HI) patched by each handler to point to the NEXT
; handler in the cycle.  On-disk initial value is $6C3F (STEP1).  Each
; handler:
;
;   1. Writes the lo/hi of the next step's address into
;      SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_LO/HI (the $6BE8 JMP operand).
;   2. Patches SMC_DS_SRC_LO/HI (the DRAW_SPRITE source pointer
;      operand) with its pose's level-data sprite
;      pointer, indexed by Y (perspective-frame index).
;   3. JSR DRAW_SPRITE, then RTS back to SPECIAL_DRAW's caller.
;
; The six poses visit sprite-table offsets {0, 7, 14, 21, 14, 7}, a
; palindromic cycle (0 -> 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 2 -> 1 -> 0 -> ...) giving
; a 6-frame walking animation from four distinct poses.  The cycle
; point persists across activations because nothing resets the SMC
; bytes at rearm --- after defeat/restart, drawing resumes from
; wherever the last cycle left off.
; ---------------------------------------------------------------------

SPECIAL_BODY_STEP1:
        ; Pose 0 (offset 0); next = STEP2
        LDA #<SPECIAL_BODY_STEP2
        STA SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_LO
        LDA #>SPECIAL_BODY_STEP2
        STA SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_HI
        LDA SPECIAL_BODY_POSE0_LO,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA SPECIAL_BODY_POSE0_HI,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        RTS

SPECIAL_BODY_STEP2:
        ; Pose 1 (offset 7); next = STEP3
        LDA #<SPECIAL_BODY_STEP3
        STA SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_LO
        LDA #>SPECIAL_BODY_STEP3
        STA SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_HI
        LDA SPECIAL_BODY_POSE1_LO,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA SPECIAL_BODY_POSE1_HI,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        RTS

SPECIAL_BODY_STEP3:
        ; Pose 2 (offset 14); next = STEP4
        LDA #<SPECIAL_BODY_STEP4
        STA SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_LO
        LDA #>SPECIAL_BODY_STEP4
        STA SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_HI
        LDA SPECIAL_BODY_POSE2_LO,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA SPECIAL_BODY_POSE2_HI,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        RTS

SPECIAL_BODY_STEP4:
        ; Pose 3 (offset 21); next = STEP5 (cycle apex)
        LDA #<SPECIAL_BODY_STEP5
        STA SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_LO
        LDA #>SPECIAL_BODY_STEP5
        STA SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_HI
        LDA SPECIAL_BODY_POSE3_LO,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA SPECIAL_BODY_POSE3_HI,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        RTS

SPECIAL_BODY_STEP5:
        ; Pose 2 again (mirror of STEP3); next = STEP6
        LDA #<SPECIAL_BODY_STEP6
        STA SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_LO
        LDA #>SPECIAL_BODY_STEP6
        STA SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_HI
        LDA SPECIAL_BODY_POSE2_LO,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA SPECIAL_BODY_POSE2_HI,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        RTS

SPECIAL_BODY_STEP6:
        ; Pose 1 again (mirror of STEP2); next = STEP1 (wrap)
        LDA #<SPECIAL_BODY_STEP1
        STA SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_LO
        LDA #>SPECIAL_BODY_STEP1
        STA SMC_SPECIAL_BODY_HI
        LDA SPECIAL_BODY_POSE1_LO,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA SPECIAL_BODY_POSE1_HI,Y
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        RTS
@ %def SPECIAL_BODY_STEP1 SPECIAL_BODY_STEP2 SPECIAL_BODY_STEP3 SPECIAL_BODY_STEP4 SPECIAL_BODY_STEP5 SPECIAL_BODY_STEP6

<<special inactive draw>>=

        ORG $6CDB
SPECIAL_INACTIVE_DRAW:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Small $02x$06 ``peek'' marker drawn while the special slot
        ; is in its inactive countdown phase ($AB == 0).  The tick is
        ; cycling $AC as an 8-bit counter and $AD stays (seeded
        ; by SPECIAL_REARM), so the sprite's screen position is
        ; effectively fixed by the slot's row-anchor $AE plus the
        ; perspective-transformed index in ZP_SPECIAL_Y.  Tail-jumped to from
        ; SPECIAL_DRAW's $6B4B.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_SPECIAL_ROW, ZP_SPECIAL_POS+1
        ;   SPECIAL_PEEK_LO/HI --- per-level sprite pointer
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_SPRITE_W/H/X/Y, SMC_DS_SRC_LO/HI.
        ; Clobbers: A, X

        LDA #$02
        STA ZP_SPRITE_W                 ; W = 2
        LDA #$06
        STA ZP_SPRITE_H                 ; H = 6
        LDA ZP_SPECIAL_ROW
        STA ZP_SPRITE_Y                 ; Sprite row = row anchor
        LDX ZP_SPECIAL_POS+1            ; $AD (stays 0 during inactive)
        LDA PROJ_SCREEN_COL,X
        STA ZP_SPRITE_X                 ; Sprite col via PROJ table
        LDA SPECIAL_PEEK_LO             ; Un-indexed
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_LO
        LDA SPECIAL_PEEK_HI
        STA SMC_DS_SRC_HI
        JSR DRAW_SPRITE
        RTS
@ %def SPECIAL_INACTIVE_DRAW

\section{Companion slot: per-frame tick + draw}

[[COMPANION_UPDATE]] is the per-frame tick-plus-draw routine
for a \emph{pair} of ``companion'' slots (indices 0 and 1) --- the
hostile walker-creatures that patrol the perspective floor,
occasionally climb to another floor, and damage the player on contact.
Despite the name inherited from [[DRAW_ENTITIES]] phase~4 (which draws
a small [[$01]]x[[$02]] marker for each slot), these slots do \emph{not}
help the player; the draw inside this routine renders the full body
sprite, runs a player-catch hit-box that sets [[ZP_HIT_FLAG]],
and contains an entity-proximity gate that triggers the floor-climb
drift phase.

\paragraph{Gate.}  The whole routine is gated on
[[ZP_COMPANION_GATE]]:
[[BPL]]-guarded, so only the positive value [[$01]] (set by
[[DIFFICULTY_UPDATE]] at any tier above minimum) allows the slots to
run.  The minimum tier and [[DIFFICULTY_RESET]] both set [[$33]] to
[[$FF]] ([[BMI]]), suppressing the subsystem.

\paragraph{Two parallel slots.}  The outer loop runs X=1, then X=0,
over parallel per-slot byte arrays in zero page:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{l|l|l|l}
ZP byte & Slot 0 & Slot 1 & Meaning \\
\hline
[[$B3,X]] & [[$B3]] & [[$B4]] & State: [[$00]] inactive, [[$01]]..[[$7F]] active, [[$FF]] drift \\
[[$B1,X]] & [[$B1]] & [[$B2]] & Direction: [[$01]] right, [[$FF]] left, [[$00]] treated as right \\
[[$11,X]] & [[$11]] & [[$12]] & World-X low byte (16-bit, 0..[[$0352]]) \\
[[$13,X]] & [[$13]] & [[$14]] & World-X high byte (stays in 0..[[$03]]) \\
[[$15,X]] & [[$15]] & [[$16]] & Floor-row Y anchor \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The same bytes are the [[ZP_COMPANION_COL]]/[[OFF]]/[[ROW]] arrays
read by [[DRAW_ENTITIES]] phase~4; see the cross-reference note
below.

\paragraph{Three-state slot machine.}  On entry to the per-slot body:
[[ZP_COMPANION_STATE]]~=~[[$00]] (inactive) re-activates the slot by writing [[$01]] and
falls through to the draw preamble; [[ZP_COMPANION_STATE]]~$<$~0 (drift)
jumps to the floor-climb handler; [[ZP_COMPANION_STATE]]~$>$~0 (active)
decrements or increments the 16-bit world-X by 3 per frame depending
on the direction byte, with a $\sim$5\% PRNG-gated chance of flipping
direction each frame.  When the counter wraps past [[$0352]] (positive
direction) or below [[$003E]] (negative direction), the slot
\emph{rearms}: direction flips, and the row reseats to the player's
current-floor threshold [[FLOOR_THRESH]]\([[$0A]]\) \(+\) [[$0B]].

\paragraph{Drift phase = floor-climb.}  Reaching one of the three
floor-anchor Y rows [[$63]]/[[$8B]]/[[$B3]] triggers the transition back to
active: the row backs off by 4, the 16-bit world-X shifts by 3 in
the current direction (so the companion ``emerges'' at a slightly
different world-X on the new floor), state becomes [[$01]].  While in
drift (state [[$FF]]) the companion's row advances by 4 pixels per frame
(no PRNG gate, no direction flips, no player-catch test), giving a
clean monotonic climb.

\paragraph{Entity-proximity drift trigger.}  The active-phase tick
walks the hit-entity active table [[ENTITY_HIT_STATE]],X
(bounded by [[ZP_HIT_MAX]]) looking for the first positive entry,
and compares its [[ENTITY_HIT_ROW]],X \(-\) [[$08]] against the
companion's own row.  When both match \emph{and} the companion's
screen-X (perspective-transformed through
[[PERSPECTIVE_XOFF_LO/HI]]) falls in [[$40]]..[[$46]], the companion
enters drift (row \(+\)= 4, state = [[$FF]]).  Outside that centre
band, a direction-specific \emph{deactivation} window
([[$30]]..[[$37]] for +direction, [[$50]]..[[$57]] for -direction) sets state
to [[$00]], ending the patrol.

\paragraph{SMC-chained 3-pose walk cycle.}  The active-phase body
draw uses two separate SMC chains (one per direction), each cycling
through three sprite pointer tables.  A trampoline
[[COMPANION_POS_TRAMP]] (positive direction) or
[[COMPANION_NEG_TRAMP]] (negative direction) dispatches to
the next pose; each pose's handler patches the trampoline's operand
bytes to point to the successor, loads the pose pointer from a
per-level sprite table at [[COMPANION_NEG_POSE1_LO]]/[[COMPANION_NEG_POSE2_LO]]/[[COMPANION_NEG_POSE3_LO]] (for \-direction) or
[[COMPANION_POS_POSE1_LO]]/[[COMPANION_POS_POSE2_LO]]/[[COMPANION_POS_POSE3_LO]] (for \+direction), patches
[[SMC_DS_SRC_LO]]/[[HI]] inside [[DRAW_SPRITE]], and [[JSR]]s.  On
a cold start the on-disk trampoline operands target
[[COMPANION_POS_POSE1]] and [[COMPANION_NEG_POSE1]] respectively
(pose~1 for each direction).

\paragraph{Player-catch.}  After drawing, the routine tests the
companion's screen-X against the [[$40]]..[[$4F]] window and the player's
row [[ZP_PLAYER_COL]] against the companion's row
[[ZP_COMPANION_ROW]],X in a [[$1A]]-tall band; overlap writes [[$FF]] to [[ZP_HIT_FLAG]],
signalling a player hit.  Drift-mode draws skip the
player-catch, so climbing companions are safe to pass.

\paragraph{Cross-reference to [[DRAW_ENTITIES]] phase~4.}  The same
ZP bytes [[$11]]/[[$13]]/[[$15]] that this routine treats as 16-bit world-X
and row are re-interpreted by phase~4 of the entity-draw dispatcher
as a perspective-projection index and a [[$B9]]-table offset, drawing a
small [[$01]]x[[$02]] marker sprite from [[COMPANION_GRID_SPR_LO]] at the companion's
projected screen position.  Phase~4's [[ZP_COMPANION_COL]],
[[ZP_COMPANION_OFF]] and [[ZP_COMPANION_ROW]] are
therefore aliases of this routine's [[ZP_COMPANION_POS_LO]],
[[_HI]] and [[_ROW]].

\paragraph{Activation is unconditional.}  The state-[[$00]] inactive
path simply writes [[$01]] to [[$B3,X]] and falls into the draw
preamble, so both slots self-activate on the first frame that
[[$33]] \(\ge\) 0.  Nothing in this routine ever clears state back to
[[$00]] except the direction-specific deactivation window during the
entity-proximity check; thus companions are effectively always
present once the score-tier unlocks them.

\paragraph{Sprite art.}  Figure~\ref{fig:companion_sprites} shows all
42 companion body frames: six pose/direction combinations (the three
negative-direction poses [[N1]]/[[N2]]/[[N3]] in rows~1--3, then the
three positive-direction poses [[P1]]/[[P2]]/[[P3]] in rows~4--6),
each with seven perspective frames.  The body sprite is $[[$04]]\times
[[$08]]$ bytes ([[ZP_SPRITE_W]]~=~[[$03]], [[ZP_SPRITE_H]]~=~[[$08]]) with 32
bytes per frame.  The SMC walk cycle at
[[COMPANION_POS_TRAMP]]/[[COMPANION_NEG_TRAMP]] visits poses
1 $\to$ 2 $\to$ 3 $\to$ 1 on successive frames for whichever
direction the slot is moving.  Sprite bytes live at
[[$9DB1]]--[[$A2F0]] in the swappable level-data region.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
