\section{PILLAR\_SPR frames ([[$7700]]--[[$7AD3]])}

The first seven frames of the sprite-pixel region are the
[[PILLAR_SPR_DATA_0]] through [[PILLAR_SPR_DATA_6]] animation cycle
for the six fixed-position pillar landmarks drawn by
[[REFRESH_PILLARS]] once per frame.  The matching 16-bit pointer
table is [[PILLAR_SPR_LO]] / [[PILLAR_SPR_HI]] (seven entries each),
and the [[ZP_SPRITE_XREF]] walking-animation index (0..6) cycles
through the seven frames in sync with the player's footfall cadence.

\paragraph{Format.}  Each frame is a 4-column $\times$ 35-row
column-major sprite (140 bytes), consumed by [[INTERLACE_BLIT_P1]] /
[[INTERLACE_BLIT_P2]].  Columns are stored rightmost-first: frame
bytes [[$00]]--[[$22]] drive the right-most painted screen column,
[[$23]]--[[$45]] drive the column one left of that, [[$46]]--[[$68]]
the column two left, and [[$69]]--[[$8B]] the left-most.  Each
source byte paints simultaneously into three perspective bands (rows
72--106, 112--146, 152--186), so the visible sprite is a 28-pixel
wide vertical tri-strip.

\paragraph{Animation.}  The seven frames are near-identical fluted
columns with subtle shading variations on the capital, shaft, and
base; cycling through them at the player's footfall rate produces a
shimmer effect that sells the pillars as 3-D landmarks despite their
fixed screen positions.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{images/pillar_sprites.png}
\caption{The seven [[PILLAR_SPR_DATA]] frames, rendered as the top
perspective band (rows 72--106).  Drawn by [[REFRESH_PILLARS]] via
[[INTERLACE_BLIT_P1]]/[[INTERLACE_BLIT_P2]] into bands 0/1/2
simultaneously.  Frame index = [[ZP_SPRITE_XREF]] (the shared
walking-animation slot).}
\label{fig:pillar_sprites}
\end{figure}

