@ \chapter{Level 1 swappable data}

[[level1.bin]] is the flat memory image loaded from tracks 5--9
when the game selects level~1.  It is extracted from the [[.dsk]]
by [[.claude/scripts/extract_level1.py]] (phase~0 of the loader's
[[PAGE_TABLE_RELOAD]]) and covers the full address window
[[$0000]]--[[$BDFF]] (48640 bytes).  Only the ``level-1 swappable pages''
hold real bytes; every non-level page stays at [[$00]]:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[$0200]] (1 page) --- initial game-data tables restored by
  [[FIRST_BOOT]] from [[ZP_SAVE]].
\item [[$1300]]--[[$18FF]] (6 pages) --- per-level attract/beam code
  (already documented in [[drol.bin]]: [[BEAM_UPDATE]],
  [[ENEMY_A_ADVANCE]], [[ENEMY_A_DRAW]],
  [[ATTRACT_ANIM_1]]..[[ATTRACT_ANIM_4]]).
\item [[$6700]]--[[$72FF]] (12 pages) --- per-level game-engine and
  attract entry code (already documented in [[drol.bin]]:
  [[LIFE_LOST_HANDLER]], [[ATTRACT_LOOP]],
  [[START_ATTRACT]]; earlier pages hold enemy-AI data).
\item [[$7500]]--[[$7AFF]] (6 pages) --- screen-row lookup tables and
  sprite sub-sections consumed by the draw routines.
\item [[$8C00]]--[[$BDFF]] (50 pages, \emph{not} present in
  [[drol.bin]]) --- the bulk of the level-1 content: per-level
  sprite tables ([[ATTRACT_SPR_LO]] / [[ATTRACT_SPR2_LO]]
  with pointers into the [[$B500]]--[[$BC]]\textit{xx} sprite-pixel
  data labelled as [[ATTRACT_SPR_0_DATA]],
  [[SPRITE_TABLE_A_BODY_DATA]], [[SPRITE_TABLE_B_DATA]], etc.), the
  ``Broderbund'' attribution strip at [[BRODERBUND_LOGO_SPR_DATA]],
  and the end-of-game
  handler [[GAME_OVER]].
\end{itemize}

All of the shared pages ([[$0200]], [[$1300]]--[[$18FF]], [[$6700]]--[[$72FF]],
[[$7500]]--[[$7AFF]]) match [[drol.bin]] byte-for-byte because
[[drol.bin]] is itself a snapshot taken after the loader has
deposited the level-1 pages into their run-time addresses.  The
only pages unique to [[level1.bin]] are [[$8C00]]--[[$BDFF]], the
high bank that the game only ever sees after level-1 loading
completes.

\section{Structure}

The [[level1]] target is maintained separately from
[[drol]] so we can verify the on-disk level bytes in isolation.
Most of the image is still raw [[HEX]] blobs at this stage; the
plan is to replace them one chunk at a time as level-specific routines
are reverse engineered.

Chunks that also live inside [[drol.bin]] (e.g.\ [[START_ATTRACT]],
[[ATTRACT_LOOP]], [[LIFE_LOST_HANDLER]]) could in principle be shared
between the two collections via chunk references.  For now, the
[[level1]] target inlines the exact same bytes as a raw
[[HEX]] blob so the two targets are structurally independent
--- a good place to experiment without perturbing the known-good
[[drol]] build.  Future sessions are expected to carve out code
chunks at [[START_ATTRACT]]/[[LIFE_LOST_HANDLER]]/[[ATTRACT_LOOP]] and share them via chunk references.

\section{The attract-mode title sprite pointers}

Two pointer tables [[ATTRACT_SPR2_LO]] and [[ATTRACT_SPR_LO]]
(with their high bytes at [[ATTRACT_SPR2_HI]]/[[ATTRACT_SPR_HI]])
feed the attract-mode sprite draws:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[ATTRACT_SPR2_LO]]/[[ATTRACT_SPR2_HI]] (4 entries) --- consumed
  by [[ATTRACT_ANIM_2]].  Entries point at [[ATTRACT_SPR2_0]],
  [[ATTRACT_SPR2_1]], [[ATTRACT_SPR2_2]], [[ATTRACT_SPR2_3]].
  Sprite byte counts are [[$2A]]/[[$2A]]/[[$1C]]/[[$1C]] respectively
  (W=2,H=14 for the first pair, W=1,H=14 for the second pair) ---
  the tall drifting silhouettes that sweep across the attract
  playfield.  Figure~\ref{fig:attract_spr2_renders} shows all four.
\item [[ATTRACT_SPR_LO]]/[[ATTRACT_SPR_HI]] (2 entries used by
  [[ATTRACT_ANIM_4]]; additional entries are consumed by
  unrelated callers).  Entries point at [[ATTRACT_SPR_0_DATA]],
  [[ATTRACT_SPR_1_DATA]].  [[ATTRACT_SPR_0_DATA]] is a 104-byte
  sprite (13 bytes/row $\times$ 8 rows; [[ATTRACT_ANIM_4]] draws it
  with W=12,H=8).  [[ATTRACT_SPR_1_DATA]] is 24 bytes (3 bytes/row
  $\times$ 8 rows, W=2,H=8).
\end{itemize}

A third consumer --- the extras-stash animation inside
[[LIFE_LOST_HANDLER]] --- uses a hardcoded [[EXTRA_LIFE_SPR]] pointer
with W=6,H=14 (98 bytes).  That sprite is the extra-life glyph the
game-over sequence ticks once per remaining extra life; it lives
directly after [[ATTRACT_SPR_1_DATA]] in the level-1 swappable region
(the 24-byte [[ATTRACT_SPR_1_DATA]] ends at [[EXTRA_LIFE_SPR_DATA]]).
Its static render
(Figure~\ref{fig:extra_life_spr}) shows three vertical stripe
columns that compose the DROL-style character silhouette.

Rendered forms of the two [[ATTRACT_ANIM_4]] sprites (the only ones
whose dimensions are derivable from static code without simulating the
attract-mode ZP animation) are in Figure~\ref{fig:attract_spr_renders}.
The [[ATTRACT_SPR_0_DATA]] shape is drawn with width~13 bytes --- the
wide ``double band'' graphic that flies across the attract screen;
the [[ATTRACT_SPR_1_DATA]] shape is a narrow 3-byte-wide creature
sprite.

