\section{End-of-game handler}

[[GAME_OVER]] is the tail of [[MAIN_LOOP]] when the per-hit
credit counter [[ZP_GAME_OVER]] goes negative (the game's ``you got
hit one too many times'' path).  [[MAIN_LOOP]]'s exit check
[[JMP]]s here when [[ZP_GAME_OVER]] goes negative.

The routine splits into four phases:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Wipe} and \textbf{reload} --- call [[SCREEN_ROW_COPY]] for
  the 192-row buffer-to-page copy (the characteristic end-of-game
  screen dissolve with per-row click track), then [[RWTS_RELOAD]] to
  fetch the next level's swappable image from disk.
\item \textbf{Reseed game state} --- zero the three on-screen score
  digits and the HUD column bounds, reseat [[ZP_PLAYER_Y]] to the
  starting floor ([[PLAYER_START_Y]]), and call [[INIT_LEVEL_STATE]] +
  [[PLAYER_MOVE_TICK]] so the reloaded level is in its fresh-start
  posture.  [[ZP_GAME_OVER]] resets to [[$01]] (one more hit-credit).
  This is the same set of writes [[GAME_START_INIT]] does for
  player-Y / score / column bounds, minus the
  [[ZP_LIVES_BCD]] / [[ZP_SCORE_HI]]..[[LO]] / [[ZP_RESTART_FLAG]]
  reset trio --- that trio is reached through the conditional
  [[JSR GAME_RESTART]] below.
\item \textbf{Page-2 to page-1 dissolve} --- a 192-row loop
  ([[X]] = [[$BF]] down to [[$00]]) that copies one hi-res row at a
  time from page~2 to page~1 via indirect [[(ZP_HGR_DST),Y]]
  ~->~[[(ZP_HGR_SRC),Y]] stores (the [[SRC]]/[[DST]] naming is
  reversed relative to [[START_ATTRACT]]'s convention: here
  [[ZP_HGR_SRC]] is the write pointer and [[ZP_HGR_DST]] is the read
  pointer), using
  [[SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_LO]] (shared low byte), [[SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI]]
  (page~1 high) and [[SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2]] (page~2 high) to
  assemble the row pointers.  Between rows it calls the Monitor
  [[MON_WAIT]] routine with [[A]]~=~[[GAME_OVER_WAIT]] for a brief
  delay and [[ROW_COPY_CLICK]] for the per-row speaker-click sfx
  (pitch = [[X]]/4).  The effect is a bottom-up reveal of the reloaded
  playfield.
\item \textbf{Continuation dispatch} --- read the dual-role byte
  [[ZP_RESTART_FLAG]] (also known as [[ZP_JOY_FLAG]]) and branch:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item [[ZP_RESTART_FLAG]]~=~0: [[JMP LIFE_LOST_RESUME]] (skipping
    [[KBDSTROBE]] clear + [[LEVEL_TRANSITION]]).
  \item [[ZP_RESTART_FLAG]]~<~0 (bit~7 set: joystick detected, or the
    [[$FF]] left by [[GAME_START_INIT]]): [[JMP MAIN_LOOP]] directly
    --- the game resumes without resetting score/lives.
  \item [[ZP_RESTART_FLAG]]~>~0: [[JSR GAME_RESTART]] (which clears
    [[ZP_LIVES_BCD]], [[ZP_SCORE_HI]]..[[LO]], and sets
    [[ZP_RESTART_FLAG]]~=~[[$FF]]), then [[JMP MAIN_LOOP]].  The side
    effect of [[GAME_RESTART]] is that [[ZP_RESTART_FLAG]] leaves the
    routine bit-7-set, so the next entry into [[GAME_OVER]] takes the
    joystick-path branch.
  \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

The routine lives in the level-1 swappable region (outside
[[drol.bin]]), so reaching it requires the bank that
[[RWTS_RELOAD]] paged in earlier to still be resident --- which it is,
since [[GAME_OVER]] itself ran the reload before the dispatch.

<<level1 game over defines>>=

; --- End-of-game state reset (see GAME_OVER body) ---
PLAYER_START_Y  = $6B           ; Floor-2 Y anchor seeded by GAME_OVER

; Monitor delay parameter passed to MON_WAIT inside the wipe loop.
; At ~60Hz the loop's A=$20 is about 17ms per row, yielding a
; ~3-second fill for all 192 rows.
GAME_OVER_WAIT  = $20

; --- Apple II ROM ---
; (MON_WAIT is already defined in the screen-row-copy defines chunk.)

@

<<level1 game over>>=

        ORG $BDA0
GAME_OVER:
        SUBROUTINE
        ; End-of-game handler: fires from MAIN_LOOP when
        ; ZP_GAME_OVER goes negative.  Runs a disk-reload,
        ; reseeds game state, dissolves from page 2 into page 1 with
        ; per-row sfx, and routes back into either the life-lost
        ; animation, MAIN_LOOP directly, or MAIN_LOOP via
        ; GAME_RESTART.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_RESTART_FLAG -- three-way continuation dispatch
        ;                      (see prose for the branch table).
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_SCORE_0..2, ZP_CLEAR_COL, ZP_PLAYER_Y, ZP_GAME_OVER,
        ;   ZP_HGR_DST, ZP_HGR_SRC, HUD_SCORE_COL, HUD_LIVES_COL,
        ;   hi-res page 1 (filled from page 2 via the dissolve),
        ;   all ZP re-seeded by INIT_LEVEL_STATE.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

; --- Wipe + reload ---
        JSR SCREEN_ROW_COPY             ; 192-row buffer dissolve
        JSR RWTS_RELOAD                 ; fetch next level's swappable pages

; --- Reseed score / HUD columns / player position ---
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_SCORE_0
        STA ZP_SCORE_1
        STA ZP_SCORE_2
        STA HUD_SCORE_COL               ; left playfield bound -> col 0
        LDA #$27
        STA ZP_CLEAR_COL                ; clear-loop max column = 39
        LDA #$28
        STA HUD_LIVES_COL               ; right playfield bound -> col 40
        LDA #PLAYER_START_Y
        STA ZP_PLAYER_Y
        JSR INIT_LEVEL_STATE            ; restore ZP from master buffers
        JSR PLAYER_MOVE_TICK            ; settle player sprite
        LDA #$01
        STA ZP_GAME_OVER                ; one hit-credit for the new frame

; --- Bottom-up page-2 -> page-1 dissolve, with per-row sfx ---
; Note: ZP_HGR_SRC and ZP_HGR_DST play the opposite roles from their
; START_ATTRACT usage here: ZP_HGR_SRC is the write (page-1) pointer
; and ZP_HGR_DST is the read (page-2) pointer.  Keeping the existing
; EQU names keeps the ZP symbol table consistent across routines.
        LDX #$BF                        ; row 191 down to 0
.wipe_row:
        LDA SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_LO,X
        STA ZP_HGR_SRC                  ; page-1 dst lo
        STA ZP_HGR_DST                  ; page-2 src lo (shared low byte)
        LDA SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI,X
        STA ZP_HGR_SRC+1                ; page-1 dst hi
        LDA SCREEN_ROW_ADDR_HI2,X
        STA ZP_HGR_DST+1                ; page-2 src hi
        LDY #$27                        ; 40 bytes per row (Y = 0..$27)
.wipe_byte:
        LDA (ZP_HGR_DST),Y              ; read page-2 byte
        STA (ZP_HGR_SRC),Y              ; write page-1 byte
        DEY
        BPL .wipe_byte
        LDA #GAME_OVER_WAIT
        JSR MON_WAIT                    ; Monitor delay (A clocks)
        JSR ROW_COPY_CLICK              ; per-row pitch-descending click
        DEX
        CPX #$FF
        BNE .wipe_row                   ; until X wraps past 0

; --- Continuation dispatch on ZP_RESTART_FLAG ---
        LDA ZP_RESTART_FLAG
        BEQ .to_life_lost               ; == 0 -> LIFE_LOST_RESUME
        BMI .to_main_loop               ; < 0  -> MAIN_LOOP direct
        JSR GAME_RESTART                ; > 0  -> full score/lives reset
.to_main_loop:
        JMP MAIN_LOOP
.to_life_lost:
        JMP LIFE_LOST_RESUME
@ %def GAME_OVER

\section{HEX chunks}

The remaining chunks are big raw-hex blocks covering each non-zero
page range.  As level-1 code and data are identified, they will be
broken out of these blobs into labelled chunks the same way the
[[drol]]-target chunks have been.

\subsection{Page 02: shared data tables and LVL\_INIT seeds}

The [[$0200]]--[[$02FF]] page in [[level1.bin]] is byte-identical to
the same page in [[drol.bin]] --- the loader's first-boot pass
drops this content from track~1 and every subsequent level-swap phase
leaves these 256 bytes untouched.  The [[drol]] target decomposes
the page into 11 labelled sub-chunks (sound tables + wipe buffer +
[[LVL_INIT_*]] seeds + dead pre-release records); the level~1 target
mirrors that decomposition with [[L1_]]-prefixed labels so the
byte-exact output matches without colliding with the authoritative
[[drol]] symbols.  Consult [[<<row copy data>>]],
[[<<page2 dead zeros>>]]..[[<<page2 dead records>>]] and
[[<<lvl init hit y data>>]]..[[<<lvl init input data>>]] in the
[[drol]] chapter for the per-field analysis; the level~1 chunks
below carry the same byte sequences and are cross-referenced for
anchor consistency.

<<level1 row copy data>>=

        ORG $0200
L1_LEVEL_INTRO_TONES:
