\paragraph{Overlap quirks.}  Three aliasing cases are worth naming:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[COMPANION_GRID_SPR]] pointer table lists 8 entries at
  [[$A2F1]], [[$A2F5]], [[$A2F9]], [[$A2FD]], [[$A301]], [[$A305]],
  [[$A309]], [[$A30D]].  The first seven are labelled as
  [[COMPANION_GRID_SPR_DATA_0]]--[[COMPANION_GRID_SPR_DATA_6]]; entry
  7 at [[$A30D]] overlaps the first 4 bytes of
  [[HUD_STRIP_SRC_DATA]], which is the primary consumer of that
  storage.
\item [[PROJ_SPR_R]] ships with 8 pointers in [[drol.bin]] at
  [[$75F7]]/[[$76F7]], but [[PROJ_FRAME_IDX]] only iterates
  [[$00]]..[[$06]], so ``frame 7'' at [[$AFD2]] is never drawn.  Its
  first byte is labelled [[PROJ_SPR_R_DATA_7_RESIDUE]]; the next 9
  bytes overlap the [[PROJ_SPR_L_LO]] and [[SPECIAL_PUFF_LO]] pointer
  tables (part of [[SPRITE_POINTER_TABLES_TAIL]]).
\item [[PROJ_SPR_L]] similarly lists pointers [[$B100]], [[$B109]],
  \ldots, [[$B136]], [[$B13F]].  The eighth pointer [[$B13F]] equals
  [[SPECIAL_PUFF_DATA_0]]; since the left-projectile draw path only
  iterates frames~0..6, the overlap never matters at runtime.
\end{itemize}

